{[%evp 0,35,19,31,68,48,60,60,58,44,44,11,23,32,37,43,65,56,56,56,47,43,40,38, 47,47,54,51,51,57,89,32,39,48,59,28,24,-4]} 1. e4 c6 { The Caro-Kann Defense historically is one of the most solid defensive repertoires - while Black temporarily allows White to grab the centre, he delivers an immediate counterstrike and in contrary to French Defense, doesn't close any of his bishops. Practice proves that it is a tough nut to crack and this is why it's so popular. After writing my trilogy for an Anti-Sicilian approach, I decided I need to write something similar about the ever-tough Caro-Kann as well. I'm going to suggest to you an easy-to-learn setup which according to several Caro-Kann experts that I've talked to, is the most annoying system for a Caro-Kann player to face! A lot of credit goes to American IM Aleksandr Ostrovskiy with whom I was working on this system, and we thought it can be a great system not only for club level but also for a more competitive player.} 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 {My suggestion - go for the Caro-Kann Exchange variation and the arising Karlsbad structure.} cxd5 { Let us stop here for a moment. It might not seem much - we've given up one of our central pawns and none of the pieces have yet been developed. Our ideal setup from here is as follows - position light-squared bishop on d3 and secure his position with c2-c3, position dark-squared bishop on f4, play Nf3, short castle, Nbd2 and Nf3-e5, followed by a potential attack at the kingside. Of course, a well-prepared player won't allow it.} ( Qxd5 $6 {Black could try to switch to Scandinavian Defense setup but this is clearly a worse version as Black has already played c7-c6 while White easily manages to setup a nice pawn duo in the centre. If someone wants to play Scandinavian, it makes much more sense to do it with the first move.} 4. c4 {in the standard Scandinavian this would be impossible as Black would have a thematic counterstrike e7-e5. White controls the centre and is ahead in development thus his advantage can't be questioned.} Qa5+ ( Qd6 5. Nf3 Bg4 6. Be2 Nf6 7. O-O e6 8. Nc3 Be7 9. Be3 O-O 10. Qd2 Bxf3 11. Bxf3 Rd8 12. Rfd1 Nbd7 13. Rac1 Qc7 14. Qe2 Re8 15. g3 Rad8 16. Bg2 a6 17. h3 Bd6 18. a3 e5 19. c5 Bf8 20. b4 exd4 21. Rxd4 Ne5 22. Rcd1 Rxd4 23. Rxd4 {1-0 (89) Grischuk,A (2733) -Feygin,M (2546) Ohrid 2009}  ) 5. Nc3 Nf6 6. Nf3  ) 4. Bd3 {an important move order - first White needs to take care that the black light-squared bishop doesn't land on f5, and the next piece he wants to develop after the useful c2-c3 is to put the dark-squared bishop on f4 to control another important diagonal.} ( 5. Nf3 Nc6 6. c3 Bf5 7. Bf4 e6 {and Black has no problems whatsoever.}  ) Nc6 {obviously, the most popular response - Black develops a knight with a tempo. There are other moves as well but developing the knight on c6 first is the most sensible thing Black can do - after all, there's hardly a better square for the black queenside knight and it keeps most of the options for Black available.} 5. c3 {Protecting the pawn on d4 and securing White from a potential Nc6-b4 outburst. If you'll get the chance, you should play Bf4 next move and develop the knights afterwards. Here we've reached the starting position of the Caro-Kann Exchange variation and Black has a variety of available options. In Chapter 2 you will learn, how to deal with the immediate e7-e5 strike in the centre, Chapter 3 will be devoted to various g7-g6 setups, preparing either Bg7 or insisting on Bf5. Chapter 4-6 will cover 4...Qc7 which doesn't allow White to play Bf4 so easily, and Chapters 7-9 we'll learn about the more modest 4...Nf6 and the most popular continuations. In this introductory chapter, I'll present to you a few ideal scenarios if Black has no knowledge about this system, he's slightly passive and what you could be aiming for.} e6 { Not the best move as Black closes his light-squared bishop but Black's position remains very solid.} ( Qc7  ) ( Nf6  ) 6. Bf4 $1 {it's important to play this before Black can play himself Bd6 otherwise you'll have a hard time to find a better square for your bishop.} ( 7. Nf3 Bd6  ) Nf6 ( Nge7 {In October 2019 the ever-creative GM Baadur Jobava tried this very weird setup twice against good GMs, and suffered two quick losses. In both games, White's responses were very convincing.} 7. Nd2 f6 8. Qe2 Bd7 9. Nb3 b6 10. h4 a5 11. Nd2 ( 12. a3 h5 13. Nh3 Kf7 14. O-O-O Nf5 15. f3 Qc8 16. Kb1 Nce7 17. g4 Ba4 18. Ka2 Nxh4 19. Rdg1 hxg4 20. fxg4 Nhg6 21. Bd6 Qd7 22. Bxe7 Bxe7 23. Qf2 Rh6 {1-0 (22) Tari,A (2630) -Jobava, B (2617) European Team Championships 2019}  ) a4 12. a3 h5 13. O-O-O Kf7 14. Nh3 b5 15. Nf3 Kg8 16. Kb1 Na5 17. Bxb5 Nc4 18. Ka1 Ng6 19. Bxc4 dxc4 20. Qxc4 Rc8 21. Qd3 Qe8 22. Rhe1 Bb5 23. Qe4 Bc4 24. d5 e5 25. Nd2 Bb5 26. Bg3 Bd7 27. f4 f5 28. Qb1 e4 29. d6 Rh6 30. Ng5 Nh8 31. Ndxe4 fxe4 32. Qa2+ Be6 33. d7 Qxd7 34. Rxd7 Bxa2 35. Kxa2 {1-0 (35) Ganguly,S (2658) -Jobava,B (2617) FIDE Grand Swiss 2019}  ) 7. Nf3 Be7 {a standard response from a player who's unaware of the dangers that this line can pose to him. Black is too passive.} ( Bd6 {is a better response but White has an advantage also here due to the better light-squared bishop and the outpost on e5.} 8. Bxd6 Qxd6 9. Qe2 $1 {taking control of the e5 square - Black might want to free his bishop by the thematic e6-e5 push.} O-O 10. O-O $14 b6 {of course, Black has better continuations here but let me just illustrate your game plan here.} 11. Ne5 Bb7 12. Nd2 Qc7 13. f4 { and White's attack at the kingside is starting to look menacing.} g6 14. g4 {a standard idea to develop an initiative at the kingside - the plan is not to play f4-f5 but g4-g5, thus taking control of all Black's squares, and also securing the knight's position on e5 against f7-f6 threats.} Rae8 15. Rae1 Nd7 16. g5 $1 $16 { a complete dominance of White's pieces - every single piece is eyeing for an attack at the kingside, and Black has no counterplay.}  ) 8. O-O {White's advantage should be obvious - he has better bishops and a beautiful outpost on e5 which will accelerate a kingside attack once Black will make a short castle.} O-O 9. Nbd2 {a note here - you want to consider to include h2-h3 first to deal with the unorthodox Nf6-h5 outburst, challenging your bishop's position. You don't want to trade it for the knight by playing Bg3 so Be3 is going to be the only option and then the knight on h5 will feel awkward. With the inclusion of h2-h3, the bishop could stay on the h2-b8 diagonal and safely retreat to h2. However, it's a whole tempo and can take away a potential square for your rook if you're looking towards a kingside attack!} ( 10. h3  ) b6 ( Nh5 10. Be3 Qc7 11. g3 $1 f5 12. Ne5 Nf6 13. Ndf3 $14  ) 10. Re1 Bb7 11. Ne5 { if you can manage to get this or a similar position, this is a one sided game - White's attack can develop very quickly from here. Just don't miss any Nf6-e4 counterstrikes in the center.} Nxe5 12. dxe5 Nd7 13. Qg4 {and we've reached some sort of French defense position with a typical White's attack at the kingside.} Re8 14. Nf3 Nc5 15. Bc2 {a perfect place for your light-squared bishop.} g6 ( Bf8 $4 {always keep an eye for the following thematical sacrifice!} 16. Bxh7+ $1 Kxh7 17. Ng5+ Kg8 18. Qh5 $18  ) 16. Bh6 Bf8 17. Bxf8 Rxf8 18. h4 $16 { White has a number of ways to increase pressure at the kingside and at any given moment he can just switch to a positional game.}  *

