1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 e5 $5 {I find it odd that this logical move has been played so rarely - it is a pretty reasonable continuation as Black fights for the centre. Although Black is trying to be active, he voluntarily creates an isolated pawn - something that White can press on for a very long time.} ( Nf6 6. h3 e5 7. dxe5 Nxe5 8. Nf3 Nxd3+ 9. Qxd3  ) 6. dxe5 Nxe5 7. Bb5+ {By far, the simplest and the best continuation which promises White a small edge in all of the lines.} ( 8. Qe2 $5 {is a tricky alternative that can be useful to know. Because of the simple f2-f4 threat to win a piece White forces Black to position the queen on the awkward e7 square, slowing down his development. If Black plays it out accurately, he should have a reasonable game, yet nowhere a full equality.} Qe7 9. Bb5+ Bd7 ( Nc6 10. Be3 $1 { a good try to cause Black some practical problems - with the queens on the board Black has to be accurate with his development. The motif might be available also in other lines as well.} Nf6 11. h3 { a good prophylaxis against a future Nf6-g4 threat.} a6 12. Bd3 Ne5 13. Nf3 {normally White would want to keep his light-squared bishop but in case of a retreat Ne5-c4 was a serious threat.} Nxd3+ 14. Qxd3 Qe4 15. Qd4 $1 Be7 16. Nbd2 Qxd4 17. Nxd4 O-O 18. O-O {White can push this position forever - essentially he has a good knight vs a bad bishop.}  ) 10. Bf4 $1 $146 {this logical move apparently is a novelty} ( 11. Bxd7+ {this most played move actually is an inaccuracy, as the practice already shows!} Kxd7 $1 { a fantastic move which immediately gives Black a great game. The two threats of Nd3+ and Nc4 are difficult to parry simultaneously and as it happens, the "unsafe" placement of the black king is irrelevant.} ( Nxd7 12. Be3 Qe6 13. Nf3 Bc5 14. Nd4 Bxd4 15. Bxd4 Ne7 16. Na3 $14 {probably is something that a White player would typically expect after exchanging the bishops.}  ) 12. Qb5+ ( 13. Be3 Nc4 14. Nd2 Nxe3 15. fxe3 Re8 16. O-O-O Kc8 $11 {1-0 (43) Savic,M (2515) -Jovic,S (2313) Novi Sad 2017.}  ) Kc7 ( Kc8 $5  ) 13. Bf4 g5 $1 14. Bxe5+ Qxe5+ 15. Ne2 Re8 {1-0 (53) Nabaty,T (2654) -Lei,T (2514) Riga 2017. Doesn't look like an achievement for White - the pin is very annoying.}  ) Bxb5 {the most logical continuation but Black has other options as well.} ( O-O-O $5 11. Bxd7+ Nxd7 12. Nd2 Ngf6 {no matter what Black plays here, none of the continuations feel like full equality for him.} 13. Be3 ( 14. O-O-O $5 Qxe2 15. Nxe2 Bc5 16. f3 Rhe8 17. Ng3  ) Qe6 14. Ngf3 Bc5 15. Nd4 Bxd4 16. Bxd4 Rhe8 17. Qxe6 Rxe6+ ( fxe6 18. f4 e5 19. fxe5 Nxe5 20. O-O-O {and Black doesn't have a full equality, White's play is easier.}  ) 18. Kf1 Rde8 19. g3 Re2 20. Rd1 R2e6 21. Kg2 $14  ) ( Nf3+ $5 {it's a spectacular shot but nothing much more.} 11. Kf1 $1 ( 12. Nxf3 Bxb5 13. Qxe7+ Nxe7 $1 14. Nd4 Bd7 15. Nd2 Ng6 16. Bg3 f5 $1 $11  ) Qxe2+ 12. Bxe2 Nxg1 {can you imagine if you ever saw this position - how did the knight get on g1?} 13. Kxg1 Bc5 14. Nd2 Nf6 15. Nb3 Bb6 16. g3 Ne4 17. Nd4 $14  ) 11. Qxb5+ Nc6+ 12. Ne2 Nf6 13. O-O Qd7 14. Nd2 Be7 15. Nf3 O-O 16. Rad1 {and White is pressing.}  ) Nc6 ( Bd7 $6 {is not playable because after} 8. Qxd5 {White has a healthy extra pawn.}  ) 8. Nf3 {the arising position has a lot of resemblance with some lines in the French Defense (1.e4 e6 2.d4 d5 3.Nd2 c5 4. Ngf3 Nc6 5.exd5 exd5 6.Bb5 cxd4 and so on) thus if you're familiar with the core ideas, they perfectly work also here. White's plan is to block the black d-pawn at d4 and at the right time later - pressure it.} Nf6 {probably this is the most reasonable continuation but Black might get cold feet regarding his d5 pawn's well-being after Bc1-g5.} ( Bc5 9. O-O Nge7 {might be another way for Black to finish his development and take care of the annoying Bc1-g5 threat as now it's threatening nothing. However, the black knight on e7 feels more passive than on f6 and it doesn't control the e4 square.} 10. Nbd2 a6 11. Bd3 O-O 12. Nb3 {This is the standard placement of white pieces - White would love to trade Black's dark-squared bishop if there's a possibility. It's also important to note that with the black knight on e7 Black can't go Bc8-g4 in one go because of a small tactical trick - Bxh7+ and Ng5+.} Bb6 {keeps at least some temporal control of the d4 square but is not creating any threats.} ( Bd6 13. Re1 {Black is still not threatening with Bg4 so White has time to make good and active moves. There's no need to rush with h2-h3 as Black might opt for Bc8-f5 and then the h2-h3 move will feel like a waste of time.} h6 14. h3 {now, of course, Bg4 is something that White should reckon with.} Bf5 15. Be3 $14  ) 13. Re1 { There might be a scenario where White will immediately go for Nbd4 or Nfd4 and then capture on d4 with a pawn in the end, but in most occasions, it will simplify Black's defense. It's better to make sure that the d4 square is occupied with a light piece.} h6 ( Bg4 $2 14. Bxh7+ Kxh7 15. Ng5+ Kg8 16. Qxg4  ) ( {or} Bf5 14. Be3 $14  ) 14. Be3 Bc7 15. h3 {probably it's a good idea to limit Black's potential active ideas with Bc8-g4 now that White no longer has the trick of Bxh7+} Bf5 16. Bc5 Bd6 17. Bxf5 Nxf5 18. Qc2 Nfe7 19. Bxd6 Qxd6 20. Rad1 $14 {1-0 (41) Pavasovic,D (2495) -Podkriznik,G (2295) Krsko 1997}  ) 9. O-O Be7 {a more careful move - now Bg5 makes little sense as it's not threatening with anything.} ( Bc5 {is seemingly more active but after} 10. Bg5 { White already forces Black to be careful and after} Be6 ( O-O 11. Bxf6 gxf6 12. Nbd2 Ne5 13. Nb3 Bb6 14. Re1 Bg4 15. Be2 Be6 16. Qd2 Kh8 17. Nbd4 Rg8 18. Nh4 Qf8 19. g3 $14 {1-0 (34) Smerdon,D (2470) -Van Tilbury,C (2280) Dresden 2008}  ) 11. Nd4 {feels quite unpleasant for Black, for example,} Rc8 12. Bxc6+ $1 bxc6 13. Qe2 Qe7 ( Bxd4 14. cxd4 O-O 15. Nc3 $14  ) 14. Re1 O-O 15. Nd2 {White has the better prospects.}  ) 10. Re1 ( 11. h3 O-O 12. Be3 Ne4 13. Nbd2 Bf5 14. Nd4 Nxd4 15. Bxd4 Bd6 16. Nf3 a6 17. Bd3 Re8 18. Re1 Bc7 19. c4 Re6 20. cxd5 Qxd5 21. Rc1 Qd6 22. Bc4 Re7 23. Be3 $14 {1/2-1/2 (45) Lobanov, S (2239) -Yakubboev, N (2062) Al Ain 2013}  ) O-O 11. h3 {not really a mandatory move} ( 12. Bd3 Bg4 13. h3 Bh5 14. Be3 { also looks very much reasonable. Black might consider playing a quick Nf6-e4 and the intimidating f7-f5 but will seriously weaken some of the central squares.}  ) Bf5 12. Be3 { with a roughly equal game still I would pick White. It's possible that Black could try to setup some kind of a battery with Bd6-c7 and Qd6 but since it takes so long to build it, it can't be very dangerous for White. A potential follow-up might be} a6 13. Bd3 Ne4 14. Bc2 ( 15. Nbd2 $2 Nxf2  ) Bg6 15. Nbd2 f5 ( Re8 16. Nxe4 $5 ( 17. Nd4  ) dxe4 17. Nd2  ) 16. Qe2 Qc7 17. Rad1 Bf6 18. Nxe4 dxe4 19. Ng5 Bxg5 20. Bxg5 {White should be better due to the bishop pair, as long as he doesn't allow Black to play f5-f4 without consequences.}  *

