1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 g6 {One of the most aggressive setups available in Black's arsenal - it's possible to play it at several stages, either before or after Nc6 or Nf6 but the key ideas essentially remain the same. Black wants to accomplish one of the three things: 1) Play Bc8-f5 and trade the light-squared bishops, doubling the f-pawns in the process. Usually Black intends to follow-up with e7-e6, Bd6 and sometimes even a long castle, looking for a counterplay at the semi-open g-file. White should accept the trade and double the pawns and before committing to castling prepare Nf3-e5. It will be traded, continue with dxe5 which will free an outpost on d4 for your other knight and Black's kingside will be vulnerable for a typical queens penetration Qh5. If Black will try to get rid of the knight by playing f7-f6, it will seriously compromise his pawn structure and give White easy targets. 2) prepare Bf5 manoeuvre with Nh6 first to recapture it with a knight. In this situation, it makes the most sense to retreat with your light-squared bishop to e2 and play against the now-misplaced knight on h6. If Black will try to bring it back in the game with f7-f6 and Nf7, this is the perfect time to strike in the centre with c3-c4. 3) finish the development of the kingside by fianchettoing the dark-squared bishop on g7 and decide the fate of the light-squared bishop later. White should harmonically finish the development with Bf4, Nbd2, 0-0, Re1, perhaps even h2-h3 and aim for Nf3-e5, followed by a slow attack build-up at the kingside.} 6. Nf3 {It seems that this move order is more accurate instead of the immediate Bf4 which I suggest to postpone for the time being.} ( 7. Bf4 {is the move I'd recommend after 5...Nf6 most likely is just fine also here but it gives Black a few more options because of the weakened b2 pawn and Bf8-h6 idea. For example,} Qb6 $5 8. Qb3 ( 9. Qe2 Bh6 $1  ) Bf5 $1 $146 9. Qxb6 axb6 10. Bxf5 gxf5 11. Na3 Ra5 $1 12. Nc2 ( 13. Bc7 e6 $1 14. Bxb6 Ra6 15. Bc5 Bxc5 16. dxc5 Ra5  ) b5 {I'm not sure I like this position for White because the logical a2-a3 to stop b5-b4 can run into a future Nc6-a5-c4.}  ) Bg7 ( Nh6 { this signals that Black is ready to play Bc8-f5 and recapture with a knight, not spoiling his pawn structure.} 7. O-O Bg7 ( Bf5 8. Be2 $1 { albeit this is a standard response, trying to play on the awkwardly positioned knight on h6, there is an interesting alternative in this particular moment.} ( 9. c4 $5 {right here it makes sense to open the centre since the black knight is out of business on h6.} Bxd3 10. Qxd3 dxc4 $146 ( Nf5 11. cxd5 Qxd5 12. Nc3 Qd7 13. d5 Bg7 14. Bg5 h6 15. Bf4 Ncd4 16. Ne5 Qd6 17. Rfe1 g5 18. Bg3 O-O 19. Rad1 $14 {1-0 (126) Zajic,M (2513) -Burovic,R (2316) Paracin 2017}  ) 11. Qxc4 Rc8 12. Qb3 Nxd4 13. Nxd4 Qxd4 14. Be3 Qc4 15. Qxb7 Bg7 16. Na3 Qc6 17. Qxc6+ Rxc6 18. Rac1 Rxc1 19. Rxc1 Nf5 20. b3 Nxe3 21. fxe3 Kd7 22. Rc5  ) Bg7 9. h3 O-O 10. Bf4 f6 { and now again White should make a radical decision in the center to change the character of the game to claim an advantage.} 11. c4 $1 $14  ) 8. Bf4 O-O 9. h3 Bf5 10. Be2 $1 {again, the same approach. Actually Qd2 and targeting the knight on h6 already is a threat.} f6 11. c4 $1 $146 ( 12. Na3 $6 e5 13. dxe5 fxe5 14. Bg5 Qd7 15. Nc2 Nf7 $15 {1-0 (36) Spraggett,K (2560) -Glavina,P (2425) Spain 1998}  ) Nf7 12. Nc3 dxc4 13. Bxc4 $14  ) ( Bf5 {if Black is ready to double the f-pawns, it makes sense to do it as quickly as possible because after the trade the dark-squared bishop might be better positioned at d6 and the black king will not be commited to castling at the kingside.} 7. Bxf5 gxf5 8. Bf4 {There's no need to rush with the castle - perhaps long castling will be an interesting alternative to consider.} e6 9. Nbd2 Nf6 ( Bd6 10. Bxd6 Qxd6 11. Qe2 { no matter what Black will do, White will play the next move Ne5 and reroute it to d3. If Black will capture on e5, White should take with the pawn, freeing the outpost on d4.} ( 12. Nb3 $5 { is also an interesting idea with the same concept.} Nf6 13. Nc5 Ne4 14. Nd3 Rg8 15. g3 f6 16. Qe2 O-O-O 17. O-O-O Kb8 18. Kb1 Rge8 19. Nh4 $1 $14 ( 20. Nd2 $6 {1/2-1/2 (46) Moiseenko,V (2528) -Paravyan,D (2528) St Petersburg 2016}  )  ) Qc7 ( Nf6 12. Ne5 Rg8 13. g3 Qc7 14. Ndf3 ( 15. Nd3  ) Nd7 15. Nxd7 Qxd7 16. O-O-O $14 {1/2-1/2 (45) Drazic,S (2426) -Lenic, L (2653) Bol 2014}  ) 12. Ne5 Nge7 ( Nxe5 13. dxe5 Ne7 14. O-O-O Nc6 15. f4 O-O-O 16. Kb1  ) 13. Nd3 $1 { as it is characteristic for Karlsbad structure, this is the ideal square for a knight. Not only it controls the central squares, but also guards the queenside, the b2 pawn and stops advancing forward the black queenside pawns.} O-O-O 14. g3 Kb8 15. Nf3 Nc8 16. O-O-O Nd6 17. Kb1 Ne4 18. Nfe5 { a long maneuvering game with the knights will ensue but it's not where exactly is Black's compensation for the doubled pawns. White has a pleasant small edge.}  ) 10. Ne5 Rg8 ( Bd6 11. Qe2 Qc7 12. O-O Rg8 ( Nd7 13. Nxd7 Qxd7 14. Bxd6 Qxd6 15. Nf3 O-O-O 16. b4 $1 Kb8 17. a4 Ne7 18. Ne5 Rhf8 19. Nd3 Rc8 20. Nc5 b6 21. Na6+ Kb7 22. a5 $1 $16 Rc4 $1 23. axb6 axb6 24. Nc5+ $1 bxc5 25. bxc5 $18 {1-0 (46) Ganguly,S (2638) -Bryakin,M (2426) chess.com INT 2019}  ) 13. g3 {eventually this should lead to a long maneuvering game where White's chances are better as the black kingside pawn structure is fixed and can't really move forward without creating more weaknesses.} O-O-O 14. Kh1 Ne4 15. Nd3 Kb8 16. Bxd6 Qxd6 17. Nf3 Qf8 18. Nh4 Qh6 19. f3 {of course, White should be careful not to allow sacrifices on g3. Here it doesn't work.} Nd6 20. Qf2  ) 11. g3 Nxe5 12. dxe5 Nd7 ( Ne4 13. Nxe4 ( 14. Nb3  ) dxe4 ( fxe4 14. Qh5 ( 15. f3 $1 $14  ) h6 15. O-O Rg6 16. Qe2 Qb6 17. c4 $14 {1/2-1/2 (33) Karthikeyan,M (2386) -Kunal,M (2318) Chennai 2019}  ) 14. Qh5 h6 15. O-O Qc7 16. Rad1 $14  ) 13. O-O  ) ( Bg4 {It is possible that Black might want to play this either now or a moment later. I think it's important to compare this maneuver if Black had played instead of 5...g6 the main move 5...Nf6 which I'll start to cover starting with Chapter 7. Then 6.Nf3 Bg4 can be a problem because for Black it's going to be easy to trade the light-squared bishops via h5-g6. This is why after 5...Nf6 I will be recommending you to play 6.Bf4 and postpone the development of the kingside knight but here - play 6.Nf3 immediately. The difference is that here the aforementioned bishop rerouting for obvious reasons is impossible and that's why we don't mind allow the early Bg4, or doubling the f-pawns. An additional remark - White doesn't need to hurry with h2-h3, clarifying Black's intentions as there might be a scenario when Black will retreat with the bishop to f5 and despite the fact that Black has lost a tempo, now White has a slightly weakened kingside and also at a later stage the Re1-e3-h3 now becomes impossible.} 7. O-O Nf6 8. Bf4 Bg7 9. Nbd2 O-O 10. Re1 {Probably White can't tolerate the bishop on g4 for forever but it makes sense to avoid it to keep the potential rook lift to h3 possible if Black will play Bf5 later and double those pawns.} ( 11. h3 Bf5 ( Bxf3 12. Nxf3 e6 13. Re1 { Black is risking that White will run over him at the kingside with an easy attack.}  ) 12. Bxf5 gxf5 13. Ne5 Nxe5 14. dxe5 Nd7 15. Qe2 e6 16. Nf3 $14 {also looks good}  ) Nh5 ( a6 11. Qb3 Qd7 12. h3 Bf5 13. Bxf5 gxf5 14. Ne5 Nxe5 15. dxe5 Ne4 16. Nxe4 dxe4 17. Rad1 Qc7 18. Rd5 $14  ) 11. Be3 Qc7 12. h3 Bd7 13. Nb3 Nf4 14. Bf1 {A typical maneuver - White is not interested to give up one of the bishops so easily, plus the knight on f4 lacks support.} b6 15. Ne5 $1 $14  ) ( Qc7 $5 {might be a tricky move to surprise White and stop Bf4 from happening, while still hinting at Bf5 and after the trade - e6, Bd6 and 0-0-0. However, White is not obliged to develop the dark-squared bishop to f4 at all costs.} 7. O-O Nf6 ( Bf5 $6 {this is a nice example to illustrate to you that sometimes you can drastically change your gameplan and strike in the center if your opponent is playing it out too smart.} 8. Bxf5 gxf5 9. c4 $1 {of course! It should be apparent that Black is lagging behind in development so opening the position should be a serious consideration.} dxc4 10. Nc3 $40  ) 8. Re1 Bg7 ( Bf5 $2 {now this is bad because of a paradoxical resource.} 9. Bxf5 gxf5 10. Nh4 $1 $16 {Black loses a pawn by force.} ( 11. Qd3 $5 Ne4 12. Nbd2 e6 {0-1 (37) Thipsay,B (2190) -Finegold,G (2035) London 1987}  )  ) 9. Nbd2 O-O 10. Nf1 {White should play it out as if nothing happened, and the only difference is that the dark-squared bishop is still at c1 for the time being. Either Black will play Bf5 now or he will run out of good moves very quickly.} Bf5 ( Bg4 11. h3 Bxf3 12. Qxf3 e5 13. dxe5 Nxe5 14. Qd1 Nxd3 15. Qxd3 Qc6 16. Be3 $14 {1/2-1/2 (45) Karjakin,S (2773) -Vachier Lagrave,M (2779) Saint Louis 2018}  ) 11. Bxf5 gxf5 12. Ng3 e6 13. Ng5 $1 $14 h6 14. Nh3 Kh7 15. Nh5 Nxh5 16. Qxh5 Ne7 17. Re3 $1 Ng8 18. Rg3 Kh8 19. Nf4 Nf6 20. Qh4 Qd8 21. Nh5 Nxh5 22. Qxh5 $18 {1-0 (38) Reichmann,H (2353) -Bruchmann,S (2304) Germany 2016}  ) 7. O-O Nf6 {the lines here are highly transpositional and it's possible I missed an interesting way to change the order of the moves but I hope you will at least get a better understanding how to treat these type of positions after reading this chapter.} 8. Bf4 O-O 9. Nbd2 { White wants to play Re1 and Nf3-e5, and if you will have time, also h2-h3 to secure his bishop's role in the h2-b8 diagonal. So either Black should play Bf5 at some time and double the pawns, or he should get rid of the bishop from f4, otherwise he risks running into a very passive position.} Nh5 {probably the most challenging continuation - Black should be aware of the potential problems at the kingside and should chase away the annoying bishop which helps to accelerate Nf3-e5.} ( b6 10. Re1 Bb7 11. Ne5 Nxe5 12. Bxe5 {the game is very much one sided - Black's counterplay at the queenside is light years away.} ( 13. dxe5 {otherwise it would be an interesting alternative but here specifically it runs into} Nh5 14. Bg5 d4 $1 {if White wants to recapture on e5 with a pawn, most likely he should include h2-h3 first so that the bishop can retreat to h2.}  ) Nd7 {this only helps White to accelerate his attack.} 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 14. Qg4 Nf6 15. Qg5 e6 16. Re3 Ng8 17. Qg4 Qd6 18. Rae1 Rae8 19. Rh3 Qe7 20. Nf3 Bc8 21. Ne5 Bd7 22. Rxh7+ $1 Kxh7 {1-0 (22) Olesen,M (2272) -Rasmussen,H (2119) Denmark 2006} 23. Nxg6 fxg6 24. Qxg6+ Kh8 25. Qh5+ Kg7 26. Qh7+ Kf6 27. Qg6#  ) ( Bf5 {now White switches to the same plan as described previously. The only difference here is that Black has already castled which might give White an opportunity to start an attack with Re1-e3-h3.} 10. Bxf5 gxf5 11. Ne5 Nxe5 ( e6 12. Nxc6 $5 ( 13. Nd3 {is always a reasonable alternative}  ) bxc6 13. Re1 Ne4 ( Qb6 14. Nb3 a5 15. a4 Rfd8 16. Re3 Ne4 17. Rh3 e5 18. Bh6 $40  ) 14. Nb3 $146 a5 15. a4 Qb6 16. f3 Nf6 17. Nc5 $14  ) 12. dxe5 Ne4 ( Nd7 13. Nf3 e6 14. Re1 Rc8 15. g3 Rc4 16. Nd4 Qb8 17. Qe2 a6 18. Rad1 b5 19. b3 $1 Rxc3 20. Nxf5 exf5 21. e6 Qb7 22. exd7 Qxd7 23. Qd2 Rc5 24. Be5 d4 25. Bxg7 Kxg7 26. Qg5+ Kh8 27. Qf6+ Kg8 28. Rxd4 {1-0 (33) Dresen,U (2311) -Bischof,D (2262) Germany 2005}  ) 13. Nb3 $14 e6 $4 14. f3 Qb6+ 15. Qd4 {1-0 (45) Garrido Fernandez,D (2250) -Quintas Galeano,L (2166) Catalunya 2012}  ) 10. Be3 $1 {a temporary retreat to an awkward square - either way, the bishop is contributing to White's position more than the black knight on h5.} ( 11. Bg3 $6 Nxg3 12. hxg3 {I think in general White should be unhappy about this trade and thus avoid it - the dark-squared bishop is a too important piece to trade away so lightly.}  ) Qd6 11. Re1 Nf4 12. Bf1 {of course, White should keep both of his bishops - the knight on f4 won't hold for long as White is either threatening to play Nf3-e5 next move or drive it away with Nb3 and Qd2.} Bf5 ( Bg4 13. h3 Bf5 ( Bxf3 $6 14. Nxf3 Ne6 15. h4 h5 16. g3 $16  ) 14. Ne5 {is essentialy the same as the main line}  ) ( Ne6 $146 {is computer's suggestion but for a human it makes little sense, except avoiding the Nf3-e5 threat.} 13. b4 $5 ( 14. g3 {is too risky as it will give Black a good game immediately after} f5 $1  ) Bd7 14. Nb3 b6 15. a4 { leads to a very interesting game.}  ) ( h6 13. Ne5 $1 ( 14. Nb3 g5 15. Nc5 b6 16. Nd3 Ng6 17. g3 f5 $13 {1/2-1/2 (47) Esipenko,A (2593) -Sakaev, K (2584) St Petersburg 2018}  ) Ne6 14. f4 $14  ) ( f6 {again, the moment Black is playing f7-f6 to prepare e7-e5, very often it will be a good idea to meet it with c3-c4!} 13. c4 $1 ( 14. Nb3 g5 15. Qd2 Ng6 {1/2-1/2 (29) Ozeran,V (2133) -Schubert,T (2345) Germany 2016}  ) e6 14. Rc1 g5 15. h3 Bd7 16. Nb1 $1 dxc4 17. Bxf4 Qxf4 18. Bxc4 $14  ) 13. Ne5 ( 14. Nb3 $5 b6 15. Qd2 Nh5 16. h3 $14  ) Bxe5 ( f6 $6 14. Bxf4 fxe5 15. Bg3 $1 $16 {and Black loses a pawn by force}  ) ( g5 14. Ndf3 f6 15. Bxf4 gxf4 16. Nxc6 bxc6 17. Nh4 $1 Bg6 18. Bd3 Bxd3 19. Qxd3 e5 20. Nf5 Qd7 21. f3 $14  ) 14. dxe5 Qxe5 15. Qa4 $1 ( 16. g3 Nh3+ 17. Bxh3 Bxh3 18. Bh6 Qd6 19. Bxf8 Rxf8 {is less convincing due to the king's weakness but also playable.}  ) g5 ( Nd3 16. Bxd3 Bxd3 17. Bh6 Qc7 18. Bxf8 Rxf8 19. Nf3 $14  ) 16. Nf3 Qf6 17. Nxg5 $14 {White's advantage is obvious. There are a few lines where Black is close to equality but they can be hard to find on the board. White's game remains simple and straightforward most of the times.}  *

