{[%evp 0,43,19,20,72,76,58,66,66,24,30,27,50,50,45,10,3,3,3,2,18,18,18,11,14,0, 3,-10,0,-7,3,9,8,-6,8,-3,-3,-18,19,9,15,26,30,30,30,51]} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Qc7 {one of the two main moves in this position - Black stops the immediate Bf4 from happening and keeps various position setups available for him.} 6. Ne2 { White insists on making Bf4 possible at the expense of the slightly misplaced knight on e2. From Chapter 4 to 6 I will cover the three main setups and how to meet them.} ( 7. Nf3 {the problem of this move lies with the fact that after} Bg4 $11 { Black will continue normal development and after h2-h3 can safely retreat to h5 and later to g6. It doesn't mean this position is not playable, just that Black has an excellent position.}  ) ( 7. Na3 $5 {there have been some attempts to win a tempo by forcing Black to play a7-a6 but it's not clear if the knight later on c2-e3 will be contributing more than on d2-f3.} a6 8. Nc2 Nf6 9. h3 $5 ( 10. Ne2 Bg4 11. f3 Bd7 12. Bf4 e5 13. dxe5 Nxe5 14. O-O Bd6 {looks rather harmless for Black}  ) e6 10. Nf3 b5 11. O-O Bb7 12. Re1 Bd6 $13 {0-1 (29) Kramnik,V (2812) -Fedoseev,V (2726) Dortmund 2017}  ) ( 7. h3 {for some time I was considering this old move to be a good approach for White and a good weapon in practical games until I started to get a better picture of the entire Caro-Kann Karlsbad structure and that's when I realized that after} Nf6 8. Nf3 g6 9. O-O Bf5 $1 {this is simply too good for Black.} 10. Bxf5 gxf5 11. Re1 e6 { The positional drawbacks are obvious - White has already castled short, h2-h3 is a useless and a weakening move of the white king, and Black hasn't even played Bg7 and can opt for a long castle instead.}  ) e6 { We'll start with this slightly rare and by the looks - passive move. Things are not so simple as Black wants to play Bd6, Nge7 and in the near future prepare f7-f6 and e6-e5.} ( Bg4 {will be covered in Chapter 5 and 6.}  ) ( Nf6 $6 {makes no sense as now White develops the bishop with a tempo and the queen has to retreat.} 7. Bf4 Qb6 8. Qb3 $14  ) ( e5 {similar as in Chapter 2, also here Black can opt for the quick breakthrough in the centre which will leave him with an isolated pawn.} 7. dxe5 Nxe5 8. Bb5+ Bd7 9. Bxd7+ ( 10. Qxd5 {is too risky because Black gains initiative with} O-O-O $44  ) Qxd7 10. Bf4 Ng6 11. O-O { and White will be pushing for a long time with a small but comfortable edge.}  ) 7. Bf4 {in general White should be happy to trade off the dark-squared bishops, especially if it comes together with winning a tempo.} Bd6 8. Bxd6 Qxd6 9. O-O {the order of the next two White moves probably doesn't matter, either playing Nd2 or castle first.} Nge7 10. Nd2 O-O {most likely Black has to make a short castle albeit castling long can be an interesting way to provoke hostilities.} ( Bd7 11. f4 O-O-O $146 {so far, nobody dared to try this} 12. b4 Nf5 13. Qc1 $36 { White has better prospects to start a dangerous attack. If Black will launch h7-h6 and g7-g5, most likely White can just ignore it and focus on the queenside.}  ) 11. f4 $5 { A very principled continuation to fight for the centre, slow down Black's plans for f7-f6 and e6-e5 and eye for a potential kingside attack. This will either lead Black to a game with an isolated pawn on d5, or he can opt for f7-f5 and reroute his knight from e7 to e4.} ( 12. Ng3 { An interesting alternative for a couple of tries. Typically the white knights go on f3 and g3, and with the help of the queen + bishop battery, bother Black with h2-h4-h5. However, I failed to find a good plan for White, should Black immediately play f7-f6 and e6-e5.} f6 $1 $146 { with clear intentions to play e6-e5 and guarding the h7 pawn with h7-h6 if necessary. After other continuations, I managed to convince myself that White can fight for an advantage.} ( e5 {Black can force matters in the centre but not necessarily this gives him equality.} 13. dxe5 Nxe5 14. Nb3 $5 ( 15. Nc4 $5 {a spectacular shot but perhaps it's not required. In general White should be concentrating on occupying the d4 square with one of his knights.} Nxc4 ( dxc4 $4 16. Bxh7+ Kxh7 17. Qxd6 {is usually a warm-up combination in textbooks.}  ) 16. Bxc4 Be6 17. Bb3 Rfd8 18. Ne2 Nc6 19. Re1 ( 20. Nd4 $5 Qc5 21. Nxe6 fxe6 22. Qg4 Rd6 23. Rae1 e5 { and here comes the eternal question of GMs - is this enough for White to claim an advantage? White's chances still seem better as he can start an inspired kingside attack.}  ) d4 $5 20. Bxe6 fxe6 21. Nxd4 Nxd4 22. cxd4 Qxd4 23. Qb3 Qd5 24. Rxe6 Qxb3 25. axb3 Rd2 26. Re7 $14 {1/2-1/2 (37) Praggnanandhaa,R (2520) -Nikolaidis, I (2535) Heraklion 2018}  ) N7c6 15. Be2 Rd8 { Black is threatening to exhange his weakness} 16. Qc2 Be6 ( d4 {would be playing with fire} 17. cxd4 Nxd4 18. Nxd4 Qxd4 19. Rad1 Qb6 20. Rxd8+ Qxd8 21. Rd1 Qe7 22. Qe4 g6 23. Bc4 $14  ) 17. Rad1 Qc7 18. Rfe1 {and White is going to be pressing for a long time. Ideally the g3 knight should land on d4.}  ) ( Ng6 13. Re1 $146 {Black might get to play f7-f6 and e6-e5 but White has not made any commital decisions and he can hope to press on Black's freshly created weaknesses. For example,} f6 ( Bd7 14. Nf3 a5 15. Bc2  ) 14. Qc2 Nce7 15. Rad1 Bd7 ( e5 $6 16. dxe5 fxe5 17. Nc4 Qe6 18. Bxg6 Nxg6 19. Ne3 Rd8 20. Qb3 Ne7 ( Nf4 21. Ne2  ) 21. f4 $16  ) 16. Nf3 ( 17. Ndf1 Rac8 18. Ne3 Be8 19. Ne2 Bf7 20. Qd2 Rfd8 21. Bc2 { with a lot of maneuvering included, most likely White's only chance to open the position is with c3-c4. If Black would try to stop it with b7-b5, this would seriously weaken the c5 square that White can invade with a maneuver Nd3-c5 and strenghten with b2-b4. The position is roughly balanced.}  ) Kh8 17. Qd2 {rearranging the placement of the bishop and the queen for the battery can be a great idea.} Rac8 18. Bc2 a5 19. h4 Nf4 20. Ne2 Neg6 21. Nxf4 Qxf4 22. Re3 $14 { White has an easier game and options to target the Black king.}  ) 13. Re1 {e6-e5 is inevitable - White should get ready to counter it.} ( 14. f4 {it is possible that White will have to consider this move and play it anyway. By doing this, later on Black can switch to the f6-f5 idea and move a knight to e4.}  ) e5 ( Bd7 14. Nf3 e5 ( Rae8 15. Bc2  ) 15. dxe5 fxe5 16. b4 a6 17. a4 Bg4 18. Bxh7+ Kh8 19. Bd3 Bxf3 20. gxf3 Qf6 21. Bc2 Qxf3 22. Qxf3 Rxf3 23. b5 axb5 24. axb5 Rxa1 25. Rxa1 Nd8 26. Ra8 Rf8 27. Rb8 $14  ) 14. dxe5 fxe5 15. c4 Be6 16. cxd5 Nxd5 {Black has an isolated pawn on e5 which is something that White can target, but at the same time he's very active.} 17. Nf3 Rad8 18. Ng5 h6 19. N3e4 Qe7 20. Nxe6 Qxe6 21. Rc1 Nd4 $11  ) Bd7 { with a typical French defense idea - in the next few moves Black might play f7-f6 and either threaten with e6-e5, or rearrange the bishop to e8 and g6. It's in White's best interest to stop the latter idea otherwise Black will get an excellent game.} ( Nf5 { this probably signals that Black is opting for the rerouting of the knight on e5 and that he will play f7-f5 real soon. Let's not forget about the fork on e3 as well!} 12. Qe1 Qc7 ( Bd7 13. Qf2 Rae8 14. Nf3 f6 15. Kh1 a6 {with the obvious idea to play e6-e5 next move} ( e5 {probably is playable but it can be difficult to evaluate the consequences afterwards} 16. dxe5 fxe5 17. fxe5 Nxe5 18. Nxe5 Qxe5 19. Qxa7 Ne3 20. Rxf8+ Rxf8 21. Ng3 Bc6 22. Re1 d4 23. Qxd4 Qxd4 24. cxd4 Nxg2 25. Re7 Nf4+ 26. Be4 {Black is down a pawn, but close to equality.}  ) 16. g4 Nfe7 ( Nh6 17. g5 fxg5 18. Nxg5 Nf5 19. Rg1 { should be in White's favor.}  ) 17. Qh4 Ng6 18. Qh5 Re7 ( Nce7 19. Rae1 { albeit better, this leaves Black in a passive defense as Black can forget about playing e6-e5.}  ) 19. Nh4 $1 f5 20. Nxg6 hxg6 21. Qxg6 $16 {1-0 (30) Ganguly,S (2638) -Le Roux,J (2533) chess.com INT 2019}  ) 13. Nf3 {comes together with a little trick} ( 14. g4 $5 {can lead to a sharp game if both players are up for it.} Ne3 {a very principled reply but still not mandatory} ( Nd6 15. Nf3 f5 16. Ng3 Ne4 17. Qe3 { White probably will exchange the pawns on f5, play Ne5 and organize an offensive at the g-file.}  ) 15. Bxh7+ $1 Kxh7 16. Qh4+ Kg8 17. Rf3 Nxg4 ( Nc4 {according to the engines, this is a draw everywhere but the game can be very wild. Just a sample of the lines:} 18. Nxc4 dxc4 19. g5 $1 Ne7 ( e5 20. f5 Bxf5 21. Rxf5 exd4 22. Rf3  ) 20. Rh3 f6 21. Qh7+ Kf7 22. gxf6 Kxf6 23. Re1 Kf7 24. Qh5+ g6 25. Qg5 Ke8 26. Rh7 Rf7 27. Rh8+ Kd7 28. d5 $1 Qc5+ 29. Nd4 Rf5 30. dxe6+ Kc7 $13  ) 18. Qxg4 Ne7 19. Nf1 {with good attacking perspectives as the black king is weakened.}  ) f6 {Black is cautious - he is fine to waste a tempo for the knight's rerouting on d6 and play f6-f5 afterwards.} ( Nd6 $2 14. Bxh7+ $1 Kxh7 15. Ng5+ Kg8 ( Kg6 16. f5+ $3 Nxf5 17. Rxf5 $3 exf5 18. Qh4 $18  ) 16. Qh4 Re8 17. f5 $1 Nxf5 18. Qh7+ Kf8 19. Rae1 { with a deadly attack}  ) 14. Kh1 {It's probably a good idea to include this move sooner or later as the need to open the g-file for an attack might arise, move the king in the corner to avoid any checks should Black open the center, plus Black could try to force a perpetual attack for the rook with Ne3-g4.} Nd6 15. Ng3 f5 16. Qe3 Ne4 17. a3 { as explained elsewhere, in the situation when Black has landed with a knight on e4, strengthened by the d5 and f5 pawns, the only real plan for White is to play c3-c4, with a potential idea to organize a pawn majority at the queenside with b2-b4 and c4-c5.}  ) 12. Nf3 {Now Black has to choose which approach to play.} ( 13. Qe1 {also has decent logic.} f6 14. Qg3 Rae8 ( Be8 15. Rae1 Bg6 $6 16. Bxg6 Nxg6 17. f5 $1 Qxg3 18. Nxg3 exf5 19. Nxf5 $14  ) 15. Rae1 Nd8 16. Nb3 b6 17. Kh1 Nf7 18. Ng1 Nf5 19. Qh3 N5h6 20. Qg3 Qc7 21. Nd2 Nd6 22. Qf3 f5 23. Qe2 Ne4 24. Ngf3 Nf7 25. Ne5 $6 Nxe5 26. fxe5 Qd8 27. Kg1 Re7 28. Nxe4 $6 dxe4 29. Bc2 Bc6 30. Rd1 b5 31. b3 Rd7 32. g3 Qb6 33. Qf2 Bd5 34. Rfe1 Rc7 35. Re3 Rfc8 36. Qd2 Qa5 37. b4 Qxa2 {0-1 (36) David,A (2563) -Rodshtein,M (2678) Brest 2018}  ) f6 {since Black is still threatening to play Be8-g6, White should take care of it first.} ( Nf5 13. Qd2 Qc7 14. g4 Nd6 15. Ng3 f5 16. g5 Ne4 17. Qe3 {the fate of this line depends on how White can play out this position. White's position seems to be slightly better - he has the better bishop and some chances for a direct attack against the black king. However, it's important not to rush it. Probably White should be happy to get a position with a knight against the supposedly bad bishop, either the knight standing or e5, or after the trade - on d4. For example,} a6 18. Ne2 b5 19. a3 Rab8 20. Ne5 Nxe5 21. dxe5 a5 22. Nd4  ) 13. Qc2 {Now Black has to make a commital decision.} ( 14. Qd2 Be8 15. Rae1 Bg6 $11  ) g6 {the safe move but now the black bishop will never get to g6. As far as I can see, White here has three options: 1) A well-prepared g2-g4-g5 might be an interesting idea to consider, fighting for the control of the e5 square. However, White should consider that Black can counterstrike in the center with e6-e5.2) Prepare b2-b3 and c3-c4, fighting for a strong pawn center. Black's pieces feel positioned really clumsy. 3) Improve the positioning of the pieces and try to provoke Black for more weaknesses. White should be ready that Black can play e6-e5 at any moment. This will leave him with an isolated pawn, so the circumstances and additional positional factors will be important.} ( Nf5 {seems to be a risky choice which already has been tested in a spectacular game.} 14. g4 $1 {accepting the thrown gauntlet} ( 15. Rfe1 $146 { also is interesting, and the threat of g2-g4 is still there, somewhere!}  ) Ne3 15. Bxh7+ Kh8 16. Qd3 Nxg4 ( Nxf1 {accepting the exchange looks very dangerous as White immediately starts a powerful attack, whose consequences are difficult to evaluate from afar.} 17. Bg6 $1 Kg8 18. Rxf1 Be8 ( Ne7 $6 {runs into a beautiful trick and Black has to be very careful not to lose on spot.} 19. Bh7+ Kh8 20. Ne5 $1 fxe5 21. Qh3 Ng8 22. dxe5 $1 Qb6+ 23. Nd4 Nh6 24. Bc2 $40 { with a powerful attack. For example,} Kg8 25. Qd3 $1 Rf7 26. Qh7+ Kf8 27. g5 Nf5 28. Bxf5 Rxf5 29. g6  ) 19. Bh7+ $1 ( 20. Ne5 $5 fxe5 21. Bh7+ Kh8 22. Qh3 Rxf4 23. Nxf4 exf4 24. Bg6+ Kg8 25. Qh7+ Kf8 26. Qh8+ Ke7 27. Qxg7+ Kd8 28. Bxe8 Kxe8 29. Qg8+ Qf8 30. Qxe6+ Ne7 31. g5 Qf5 32. Qxf5 Nxf5 33. Rxf4 Ng7 34. h4  ) Kh8 20. Nh4 f5 21. Bg6 fxg4 ( Kg8 22. g5 Ne7 23. Bxe8 Raxe8 24. Nf3 Ng6 25. Qd2 { this looks as a positional nightmare for Black - White's plan is very straightforward. The engines remain optimistic.}  ) 22. Bxe8 Raxe8 23. Ng6+ Kg8 24. Nxf8 Rxf8 25. Qg3 Ne7 26. Qxg4 $14  ) 17. Nh4 Ne7 18. Ng6+ Nxg6 19. Bxg6 Nh6 20. Kh1 Be8 21. Rg1 Qe7 22. Rae1 f5 23. Qh3 Rf6 24. Bxe8 Rxe8 25. Ng3 Kh7 26. Nh5 Rf7 27. Qg3 Kh8 28. h3 Ng8 29. Qg6 Nf6 30. Re2 Nxh5 31. Qxh5+ Kg8 32. Rg6 Qd6 33. Qh6 Qa6 34. Reg2 Qf1+ 35. Kh2 Ree7 36. Qh4 Qf3 37. R6g5 Rd7 38. Rh5 Rf8 39. Rh8+ Kf7 40. Rxg7+ Ke8 41. Rxf8+ Kxf8 42. Qh8# {1-0 (42) Van Foreest,L (2521) -Van den Doel,E (2605) Amsterdam 2019}  ) ( h6 $6 $146 {this move feels inferior to 13...g6 as it weakens the Black king's position and he has to be constantly careful not to miss any Bh7+ and Nf3-h4-g6 tactical ideas.} 14. Rae1 Rae8 15. Ng3 Kh8 16. Qd2 $14 { Most likely Black will play at some point f6-f5 anyway and switch to the plan bringing a knight to e4.}  ) 14. Qd2 Rae8 15. Rae1 Qc7 16. b3 { I'm not sure how critical is this particular position as both sides had plenty of ways to divert earlier. Either way, it seems that the only reasonable way for White to get a clear plan is to play c3-c4 at the right time. Perhaps it's a better idea to maneuver first and improve the piece placement to the maximum, allow the Black knight to land on e4, strengthened by the d5 and f5 pawns and only then prepare c3-c4 as Black won't be able to capture the pawn without serious positional consequences. Ideally White wants to create a protected passed pawn at the queenside with c3-c4-c5, strengthened with b3-b4. Of course, White has to anticipate Black's countermeasures b7-b6 or e6-e5 at any given time.} ( 17. g4 Nc8 18. Ng3 Nd6 19. g5 f5 20. Ne5 Nxe5 21. Rxe5 {1/2-1/2 (42) Terletsky,O (2263) -Punin,A (2259) Lvov 2016}  ) Nf5 17. c4 dxc4 18. bxc4 Na5 19. Rc1 b6 20. g4 Nh6 21. h3 Nf7 22. Ng3 {with a complex middlegame and chances for both sides.}  *

