1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Qc7 6. Ne2 Bg4 {the main move - Black stops Bf4 from happening and plans to resume normal development.} 7. O-O { in the meantime, White intends to play Qe1 next move and depending on how Black will respond, go hunting the bishop on g4.} ( 8. f3 {This is the old main line and supposedly not dangerous for Black, however it can lead to a game with an isolated pawn.} Bd7 ( Bh5 9. Nf4 { is the idea and it is my belief that White should be happy about the arising position as this is something we will be aiming for in the next chapter.} Nf6 10. Nxh5 Nxh5 11. O-O e6 12. f4 g6 13. g3  ) 9. Bf4 e5 10. dxe5 Nxe5 11. O-O Bd6 12. Nd4 Ne7 13. Na3 a6 14. Nac2 O-O ( O-O-O $5 $132  ) 15. Kh1 Rac8 $11 {0-1 (37) Semeniuk,A (2456) -Dreev,A (2639) St Petersburg 1999}  ) ( 8. Na3 $5 { this manoeuvre can be included at pretty much any given moment, should Black play early Qc7 and if the Bxa3 is not yet available. The idea is to play Nb5, followed by Bf4, threatening with Nc7+. If Black responds with the standard a7-a6, this could compromise his chances to make a long castle in the future as the a6 pawn will make a nice target. Of course, the question remains - what exactly has White gained from this extra tempo and how important it is to have the knight on c2-e3 afterwards? The traditional route of Nb1-d2-f3 is much more common.} a6 9. Nc2 e6 10. Qd2 $5 { with a creative idea to bother the bishop on g4 with either Nf4 or Ng3, gaining a two bishop advantage. The awkward queen placement is a temporary problem and will be fixed soon.} Bh5 ( Nf6 11. Ng3 Bh5 ( e5 $5 $146  ) 12. Nxh5 Nxh5 13. g3 Nf6 14. Qe2 Bd6 15. Bd2 h6 16. f4 Ne7 17. O-O-O g6 18. Rhf1 h5 19. Ne1 $1 Nf5 20. Nf3 O-O-O 21. Kb1 Kb8 22. Rc1 Qb6 23. Ne5 $14 {1-0 (72) Hou,Y (2673) -Henriquez Villagra,C (2505) Punta Arenas 2016}  ) 11. Nf4 Bg6 12. Nxg6 hxg6 13. g3 Bd6 14. Qe2 O-O-O 15. Bd2 { with an interesting middlegame and most likely the same game plan as seen in the Hou vs Henriquez Villagra game.}  ) ( 8. Bf4 Qxf4 $1 {is the idea} 9. Nxf4 Bxd1 10. Kxd1 e6 $11 {and Black has nothing to worry about.}  ) e6 { Black continues to harmonically develop his pieces and intends to develop his other bishop with a tempo.} ( Nf6 {is less played and in most occasions, it will lead to the same positions with a slightly different order of the moves, however, it does present Black a few interesting alternative options.} 8. Qe1 Bh5 {an interesting order of the moves but it changes little.} ( e6 {transforms to the main line.}  ) ( Qc8 $5 { so far it has been played only once, in a high-level GM game, but the idea is clear - taking into account that Black has delayed e7-e6, he can still trade the light-squared bishops without ruining his pawn structure. Since the trade seems to be inevitable, White should make most out of the position before it happens.} 9. Ng3 {provoking the advancement of the h-pawn if Black still wants the bishop trade to happen.} ( 10. f4 $5 $146 Bf5 11. Bxf5 Qxf5 12. Ng3 Qd7 13. f5 h5 14. Nd2 h4 15. Ne2 h3 16. gxh3 O-O-O $13 {probably it's worth to investigate this further.}  ) h5 10. f3 {here, most likely surprised by the turn of the events, Gata Kamsky didn't impress with the chosen continuation and Nikita Vitiugov with Black soon got an excellent position. I found a couple of possible improvements to explore.} ( 11. h3 $5 $146 {aiming for a positional game as the black pawn on h4 might become a long-term weakness to care about.} Bd7 ( h4 $6 {also here this manoeuvre quite doesn't work, but for different reasons.} 12. hxg4 hxg3 13. g5 $1 ( 14. f3 $6 {here is less clear as the h-file is open and White can't get to the g3 pawn so easily.} Qc7 $13  ) Ng4 ( gxf2+ $2 14. Qxf2 { and Black loses because of a deadly pin.}  ) 14. fxg3 g6 15. Rf4 $1 { forcing matters} e5 16. Be2 $3 Ne3 $1 17. Bxe3 exf4 18. Bxf4 Be7 19. Nd2 $16  ) ( Bxh3 $2 {this sacrifice doesn't work here although I'm sure Tal would approve it.} 12. gxh3 Qxh3 13. f3 h4 14. Ne2 R