 on winning a tempo can be tempting but then Black solves all of the opening problems as he manages to exchange the light-squared bishops.} Qd7 11. Nd2 e6 12. Bg3 Bg6 13. Nf4 Nh5 14. Qe2 Nxf4 15. Bxf4 Bd6 16. Bg3 Bxg3 17. hxg3 Bxd3 18. Qxd3 $11 {1-0 (49) Zierk, S (2476) -Ostrovskiy,A (2414) Charlotte 2018}  ) Bxe2 ( e6 10. Ng3 Bd6 11. Nxh5 Nxh5 12. g3 {is essentially the same what happened in Kovalev vs Svane, Aeroflot 2018.}  ) 10. Qxe2 e6 11. Nd2 Bd6 12. g3 { also doesn't change much in terms of White's plans.}  ) ( Bh5 $5 { is a very tricky move - Black doesn't want to wait and sit while White executes his plan and moves to the bishop trade immediately. Since the white queen is still on d1, for obvious reasons Nf4 is impossible. The most notable game in this line is Kovalev vs Svane from the Aeroflot Open 2018.} 8. f4 $1 {with the idea to stop the Black's desired to trade with f4-f5. It does weaken the e4 square in the process but there's no way around it if you are fighting for an advantage.} e6 9. Qe1 Bd6 10. Ng3 Nf6 ( {of course, not} Bg6 $2 11. f5  ) 11. Nxh5 Nxh5 12. g3 {this type of position is canonical for the entire database so expect to meet it frequently.} Nf6 ( g6 $5 {essentially leads to a position where Black will play Re8 first, then f7-f5, followed by Nf6-e4. Black is solid but static.} 13. Nd2 O-O 14. Nf3 Rae8 15. Bd2 f5 16. Qe2 Nf6 17. Rac1 Qb6 18. Be3 Ng4 19. Bf2 Re7 20. Kg2 Rfe8 21. h3 Nxf2 $6 22. Rxf2 h6 23. h4 h5 24. Bb5 $1 a6 25. Bxc6 bxc6 26. b4 a5 27. a3 Ra7 28. Qe1 Bf8 29. Re2 $16 {1/2-1/2 (44) Paszewski,M (2293) -Punin,A (2296) Suwalki 2018}  ) 13. Nd2 h5 14. Nf3 {it's important to limit Black's options at the kingside by timely positioning the knight on f3, stopping the h5-h4 at least for the time being.} Kf8 {a creative idea - Black is going to play g7-g6 and Kg7, strengthening the control of many squares at the kingside.} 15. b3 $5 $146 {my proposed novelty over the Kovalev vs Svane game - the bishop is going to feel much active on b