nd if Black plays it out in the best way, he does achieve an equal position in the end.} ( Bd6 $6 {the standard mistake.} 10. f3 Bh5 ( Bf5 11. Bxf5 exf5 12. Bxf6 gxf6 13. Qh4 $16  ) 11. Qh4 Bg6 12. Bxg6 fxg6 13. Bxf6 gxf6 14. Qxf6 {and Black has no compensation for the pawn - this line was already covered earlier in one of the sidelines.}  ) ( h6 $6 {a careless move} 10. Bxf6 Bxe2 ( gxf6 $4 11. f3 Bh5 12. Qh4 {and Black can resign.}  ) 11. Bxe2 gxf6 12. Bh5 {the way I treat this position, it's always better to have a bishop on h5, blocking the advancement of the h-pawn and targeting the f7 pawn, not the queen. Not surprising - the queen is considered to be a bad blocker.} O-O-O 13. g3 Rg8 14. Nd2 {with an edge for White}  ) ( Be7 $5 {seemingly Black falls into the same trap, except here he has a spectacular way out!} 10. f3 ( 11. Ng3 $5 $146  ) Bh5 11. Qh4 Kd7 $3 $146 {I give the double exclamation marks for the bravery as Black doesn't lose material on the spot. However, I mentioned earlier - early king walks are rarely good.} ( Bg6 12. Bxg6 fxg6 13. Nf4 Kf7 14. Qh3 Qc8 15. Re1 Bd6 16. Nxe6 Re8 17. Bxf6 Rxe6 18. Rxe6 Qxe6 19. Qxe6+ Kxe6 $16 {1-0 (54) Grachev,A (2203) -Maltsevskaya,A (2279) Voronezh 2018}  ) 12. Bxf6 Bg6 $3 {the point!} 13. Bxe7 Bxd3 14. Bf6 $5 ( 15. Ba3 Bxe2 16. Re1 Bd3 17. c4 $5 {again, probably the only real way to prove that Black has chosen the wrong strategy, otherwise Black should eventually equalize.} Bxc4 ( dxc4 $2 18. d5 $1 Qb6+ 19. Kh1 exd5 20. Nc3 $40  ) 18. Nc3 {and Black faces an uneasy task to bring his king to safety.} Rae8 19. b3 Ba6 20. Rac1 Kc8 21. b4 Bc4 ( Qd6 $5 22. b5 Qxa3 23. Qg3 Rhg8 24. bxa6 Qxa6 25. a4  ) 22. b5 Na5 23. Bb4 Kb8 24. Na4 Ka8 25. Nc5 $36  ) Bxe2 15. Rf2 gxf6 16. Rxe2 f5 17. c4 $1 {the Black king is in the center so some drastic action is required.} dxc4 18. Nc3 Rad8 19. d5 Qb6+ 20. Kh1 exd5 21. Nxd5 Qd4 22. Qg5 Qxd5 23. Rd2 Nd4 24. Rad1 Kc6 25. Rxd4 Qxd4 26. Rxd4 Rxd4 27. h3 Rhd8 28. Qxf5 R8d7 29. Qxh7 b5 $13  ) ( Bxe2 {if at any given moment Black decides to play it safe and gives up his bishop, essentially switch your mindset for Chapter 6!} 10. Qxe2 Bd6 11. g3 {it's standard for this type of position to stop Bd6-f4 and the bishop trade.} h6 $5 ( Nd7 12. Nd2 O-O 13. Rae1 ( 14. Nf3 Rfe8 15. Rad1 a6 16. Bc1 b5 17. a4 bxa4 18. Qc2 Nf8 19. Qxa4 Na5 20. Rfe1 Rec8 21. Ne5 $14 {1-0 (47) Kobalia,M (2601) -Lobanov,S (2515) Sochi 2018}  ) Rfe8 14. Be3 Nf6 15. f4  ) 12. Be3 ( 13. Bxf6 gxf6 14. Qh5 {otherwise this would be interesting but I believe that queen is a bad blocker and that Black eventually will get rid of it with f6-f5, Ne7-g8-f6}  ) h5 13. Nd2 h4 ( Ng4 14. Bg5 Be7 15. f4 $1  ) 14. Nf3 hxg3 15. hxg3 Ne4 16. Rae1 O-O-O ( f5 17. Ng5 $1  ) 17. Bxe4 dxe4 18. Ng5 $14  ) 10. f4 { with an incoming trap - White intends to play Ng3 next move, followed by f4-f5. Nevertheless, two games at a GM level have already been played here, and both times Black fell right into it!} ( 11. Nf4 $5 $146 {it's worth to test this move as well as it might substitute the main line!} Bg6 ( h6 $5 {if White is ambitious, he has an option to sacrifice a piece.} 12. Nxe6 $5 ( 13. Bxf6 Qxf4 $1 {the point} 14. Be5 Nxe5 15. dxe5 a6 16. Nd2 Bc5 17. g3 Qa4 {it doesn't look like Black has anything to worry about here.}  ) fxe6 13. Bxf6 gxf6 14. Qxe6+ Be7 ( Ne7 15. Bb5+ Kd8 16. Re1 $40  ) 15. Qxd5 Bf7 16. Qf5 $13  ) ( Bd6 12. Nxh5 Bxh2+ $2 ( Nxh5 13. g3  ) 13. Kh1 Nxh5 14. Be2 $1 ( 15. g3 $2 Bxg3 16. fxg3 Nxg3+ 17. Kg2 Nxf1 18. Qxf1 O-O $15  ) Nf4 15. g3 Nxe2 16. Qxe2 Bxg3 17. fxg3 Qxg3 18. Bf4 $16  ) 12. Nxg6 hxg6 13. g3 Bd6 14. Nd2 O-O 15. f4 {otherwise e6-e5 will income the next move and it's going to be difficult to claim an advantage.} ( 16. Nf3 Rae8 17. Qe2 e5 18. dxe5 Nxe5 19. Nxe5 Rxe5 20. Qd2 Rfe8  ) Nh7 16. Nf3  ) Bxe2 $1 {Black has to acknowledge the threat and finally trade the bishop. It can be a difficult move to make as Black just played Bh5!} ( h6 $146 11. Bxf6 ( 12. Bh4 $5 $146 {also looks very much interesting}  ) Bxe2 12. Bxe2 gxf6 13. Bh5 {if White can get the bishop on h5, in general he should be happy.} O-O-O 14. Nd2 Bd6 15. g3 { Black wants to reroute his knight to e4 so White will have plenty of time to organize an initiative at the queenside.}  ) ( O-O-O $2 {this can't be good.} 11. Ng3 Bg6 12. f5 exf5 13. Bxf6 ( 14. Nxf5 $146 {engines seem to like this move better.} Re8 15. Qf2 Ng4 16. Qf4 Qxf4 17. Bxf4 $14  ) gxf6 14. Nxf5 {Black is strategically busted so he has to rely on an active play.} Qb6 {there are many ways how White can secure a solid advantage, as long as White doesn't miss any tricks.} 15. Na3 $5 ( 16. Nd2 Qxb2 17. Nb3 Qa3 18. Qh4 Be7 19. Bb5 ( 20. Nxe7+ Qxe7 21. Rae1 Qc7 22. Nc5 $16  ) Bxf5 20. Rxf5 Na5 21. Qe1 Bd6 22. Qf1 $14 {0-1 (39) Heberla,B (2550) -Gholami,A (2488) Stockholm 2019}  ) ( 16. Qf2 $6 {unfortunately meets a surprise tactic} Ne5 $3 17. dxe5 Bc5 18. Nd4 Bxd3 {so this is something we want to avoid.}  ) ( 16. b4 $5 $146  ) ( 16. Qd2 $5 $146  ) ( 16. Rf2 $5 $146 Ne5 17. Qe2 Nxd3 18. Qxd3  ) h5 16. Nc2 Qxb2 17. Rb1 Qxa2 $16 {1/2-1/2 (21) Predojevic,B (2626) -Rasmussen,A (2543) Germany 2018}  ) 11. Qxe2 h6 {very accurate} ( Be7 12. Nd2 O-O 13. Rae1 {here Black risks running under a dangerous attack at the kingside.}  ) ( {or} Bd6 12. g3 ( 13. Qf2 O-O-O 14. Nd2 Kb8 15. Rac1 h6 16. Bxf6 gxf6 17. Kh1 h5 18. a3 Rhg8 19. Be2 Rg7 20. c4 dxc4 21. Rxc4 Qb6 22. Ne4 Be7 23. Bxh5 Rh7 24. Bf3 Nxd4 25. h3 Rhh8 26. b4 Qa6 27. Rc3 b6 28. Rd1 Nxf3 29. Rxd8+ Rxd8 30. Qxf3 Rd4 31. f5 e5 32. Kh2 Qb7 33. Re3 Qd7 34. h4 Qd8 35. g3 Qd5 {1/2-1/2 (34) Suarez Gomez,J (2429) -Kadric,D (2562) Evora 2019}  ) h6 13. Bxf6 gxf6 14. Qh5  ) 12. Bxf6 {I presume that White will have to take on f6 sooner or later.} ( 13. Bh4 Bd6 14. g3 O-O-O 15. Nd2 Rdg8 16. Bxf6 ( {the tempting} 17. f5 {unfortunately is met by} e5 $11  ) gxf6  ) gxf6 13. Qh5 {since the h-pawn advancement is a positional threat, White voluntarily sends the "bad blocker" to stop the pawn, and it's going to stay there until White can finish his development.} Bd6 14. g3 Qb6 $1 {again, very accurate. Black slows down White's development.} 15. Rf2 Kf8 $1 16. Kg2 { a part of rearranging the pieces - the king on g2 stands well to avoid any potential tactical tricks after Nxd4 or e6-e5.} f5 { Black is rerouting his knight to e4.} 17. Rc2 {otherwise it's difficult to develop the queenside without making commital weaknesses.} Ne7 18. Nd2 Ng8 19. Qe2 {time to go! Now the only viable plan for White is to prepare c3-c4.} Nf6 20. Nf3 h5 21. Rf1 {last preparation} ( 22. b3 h4 $1 23. Nxh4 Bxf4 {White should be ready for this}  ) Kg7 22. b3 Be7 23. c4 $13 { I'm not sure how to properly evaluate this position. Obviously White is advancing pawns at the queenside and can either try to form a passed pawn with c4-c5 and b3-b4-b5, or capture on d5, followed by Bc4 and if the knight retreats - d4-d5. Perhaps the latter choice is safer and more direct. At the same time Black is dreaming about h5-h4 and can start an improvized attack at some time with Rag8, Kf8 and h5-h4. So my most honest evaluation probably is - it's equal with chances for both sides. Black picked up a lot of the absolute best moves to get here. If you don't like the position, there are number of ways to surprise your opponent with the sidelines, presented in this chapter.}  *

