1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Qc7 6. Ne2 Bg4 7. O-O e6 8. Qe1 Bxe2 {the safest choice - since White has several tricks in his arsenal to choose from, Black can voluntarily give up his light-squared bishop to get an easier to play position. The alternatives are covered in other chapters. This setup can arise from many lines with slight differences. Sometimes Black will have already included a7-a6, sometimes the white f-pawn already will be standing on f4. I believe that the typical ideas don't change so you can recognize them already from afar.} ( Nf6 9. Bg5 Bxe2 10. Qxe2 Bd6 11. g3 {should be something similar, except the white bishop is already on g5.}  ) 9. Qxe2 Bd6 10. g3 {So far I believe everything is almost forced - White could have played f2-f4 immediately but afterwards you will be obliged to play g2-g3 anyway in order to develop your knight with Nb1-d2-f3. As far as I can see it, Black has two real options here: 1) Play Nf6 and proceed with a short castle. Afterwards, he either aims for the breakthrough in the centre with e6-e5 or to try to create some weaknesses at the queenside, by executing the typical idea b7-b5, a7-a5, b5-b4 and target the c3 pawn. 2) Play long castle and hope for an attack at the kingside with the standard h7-h5-h4.} Nf6 11. Nd2 O-O {Let's check the Black's plan No.1 - he plays it safe and opts for a positional approach. Here White has two options: either go for the aggressive f4-f4 which is pretty much straightforward but it gives up the e4 square forever, or aim for more positional manoeuvring with Nf3 -> Bg5 etc.} ( h5 12. Nf3 {the way I treat the position, the immediate h5-h4 gives Black too good position so probably it's a great idea to stop it, at least for the time being.} ( 13. f4 $5 {I played this once myself - it's quite provocative as White doesn't manage to stop the incoming h5-h4, the engines think it's equal somewhere but it can lead to some entertaining lines. Probably the main line is simply better.} h4 14. Nf3 hxg3 15. hxg3 O-O-O 16. Kg2 Ne7 ( Ng4 $1 17. Rh1 ( 18. Nh4 $6 Nh2 $3 19. Rh1 g5 20. Ng6 fxg6 21. Qxe6+ Kb8 22. Rxh2 Rxh2+ 23. Kxh2 gxf4 24. Kg2 Ka8 $17  ) Rxh1 18. Kxh1 Rh8+ 19. Kg1 ( 20. Kg2 $2 g5  ) Ne7 20. Ng5 ( 21. Ne5 {0-1 (48) Martinez Alfonso,J (2034) -Avila Jimenez,X (2159) Vilafranca del Penedes 2019}  ) Nh6 21. Bd2  ) 17. Bd2 Nf5 18. Ne5 Nh5 19. Be1 {from afar it looks risky but Black has a hard time to make any good out of this.} g6 20. Rh1 Rh7 21. Qf3 Rdh8 22. Bf2 $14 f6 $4 23. Nxg6 Nhxg3 24. Bxg3 Rxh1 25. Rxh1 Rxh1 26. Bxf5 Rc1 27. Qe3 {1-0 (26) Neiksans,A (2559) -Starostits, I (2457) Riga 2019}  ) O-O-O $6 {The plan No.2 - Black tries to hide his king at the queenside so that he can focus attacking at the kingside. I think this is a very risky approach and can backfire badly. Then again - if Black decides to stay in the centre or transfer the king to g7, it remains unclear - why did he play h7-h5 in the first place.} 13. a4 { A very easy plan - a quick march forward with the a-pawn and a direct attack at the queenside. The dark-squared bishops remain on c1, at least for the time being.} Rde8 { it makes sense to answer a queenside attack with a counter-strike in the centre.} ( h4 $6 {is interesting but the engines are not really impressed} 14. Nxh4 Rxh4 15. gxh4 Rh8 16. Bg5 Bxh2+ 17. Kg2 Nh5 18. Rh1 Bf4 19. Qf3 $16 f6 $6 20. Bg6 $1  ) ( Kb8 {hiding the king in the corner is a reasonable idea but it costs time. White can proceed with the same idea.} 14. a5 Nxa5 15. Bg5 { here the immediate b2-b4 doesn't work as Black has protected his a7 pawn. Ultimately the plan doesn't change - pressure the a-file with the heavy artillery.} Rc8 16. Ra4 Nc4 17. Rfa1 a6 18. Bxc4 dxc4 19. Nd2 Nd5 20. Nxc4 h4 21. Nxd6 Qxd6 22. c4 hxg3 23. fxg3 f6 24. Bd2 Nc7 25. Rb4 Ka8 26. Qf3 $16 {the black king is in the heavy crossfire.}  ) 14. a5 $1 {a common idea, borrowed from the Sicilian Dragon line - White sacrifices a pawn to accelerate his attack at the queenside.} Nxa5 {Sure, it's risky but what else?} ( e5 15. dxe5 Bxe5 16. Nxe5 Nxe5 17. a6 b6 18. Bf5+ Nfd7 19. h4 g6 20. Bh3 f5 21. Bg2 Nf6 22. Bf4 $16  ) ( a6 15. b4 e5 16. dxe5 Nxe5 17. b5 $40 {looks even worse for Black}  ) 15. b4 { if the a7 pawn would be protected, then this wouldn't work. An alternative is Bg5, R1a4 and Rfa1.} Nc6 16. Ba3 ( 17. Bg5 {also looks great.}  ) Kb8 ( Ne7 17. b5 Bxa3 18. Rxa3 Kb8 19. b6 $1 {opening more lines} Qxb6 20. Ne5 $16  ) 17. b5 Ne7 18. b6 $1 Qxb6 19. Rfb1 Qc7 20. Bxd6 Qxd6 21. Ne5 Rhf8 22. Ba6 b6 23. Bb7 $3 { it's not a forced but it nicely illustrates the storm that White can conjure at the queenside. Notice how Black didn't even start his offensive at the kingside.}  ) 12. f4 { White stops the e6-e5 from ever happening and intends to start a full-scale assault at the kingside. The way I see it, Black has two options - either stop the attack with the pretty much inevitable f7-f5 and reroute a knight to e4, or have cold steel nerves and proceed with a counter-attack at the queenside. For an engine it might be the best choice, however human beings usually fear of an incoming attack.} ( 13. Nf3 { with this approach White doesn't rush with closing the center and thus - permanently weakening the e4 square. White intends to provoke some weaknesses from Black's side first, and eye for a kingside attack. Black can play e6-e5 but this will lead to positions with an isolated pawn on d5. I'll present to you a couple of games which will give you a better understanding how usually White plays from here.} a6 ( Rfe8 14. Be3 {White doesn't mind if Black will play e6-e5.} g6 ( e5 15. dxe5 Nxe5 16. Nxe5 Bxe5 17. Qf3 $14  ) 15. Rad1 a6 16. a3 b5 17. Rfe1 Na5 18. Bg5 Nd7 19. Ne5 ( 20. h4 $5  ) Nc4 20. Ng4 f5 21. Ne3 Nxe3 22. Qxe3 Nb6 23. Qf3 Nc4 24. Re2 Qf7 25. Rde1 Rac8 26. h4 Bf8 27. Kg2 h5 28. Qf4 $14 {1-0 (79) Delgado Ramirez,N (2613) -Erenburg,S (2550) Medellin 2017}  ) 14. Bg5 Nd7 15. Rad1 b5 16. Rfe1 Na5 ( Rfe8 17. Bb1 Rac8 18. Qd3 Nf8 19. Kg2 b4 20. c4 {a common idea to switch to a game with an isolated pawn on d4, however White has two bishop and some space advantage.} dxc4 21. Qxc4 Qa5 22. Qe2 h6 23. Bc1 Ne7 24. Ne5 Bxe5 25. dxe5 Red8 26. Rxd8 Rxd8 27. h4 Nf5 28. h5 $14 {1/2-1/2 (46) Heberla,B (2570) -Carow,J (2437) Karlsruhe 2018}  ) 17. Ne5 Nxe5 18. dxe5 Be7 19. Bf6 $1 {a nice motif to know!} g6 ( gxf6 20. Qg4+ $1 Kh8 21. exf6 Bxf6 22. Qh5 $18  ) 20. Qg4 Rfe8 21. Qh4 Nc6 22. Re3 Bxf6 23. exf6 Qd6 24. Bxg6 $1 fxg6 25. f7+ Kg7 26. fxe8=N+ Rxe8 27. Qg4 b4 28. cxb4 d4 29. Qe4 e5 30. a3 {1-0 (29) Ragger,M (2644) -Vogel,R (2477) Czech Republic 2018}  ) a6 ( Rae8 { clearly an indication that Black will prepare f7-f5 as the other rook is left on f8. There's nothing White can do about it, so focus on improving your pieces.} 13. Nf3 Nd7 14. Be3 $146 {it makes more sense to position the bishop on e3. It doesn't do much there at the moment, but it solidifies White's position around it even more.} ( 15. Bd2 f5 16. Ne5 Nf6 17. Kh1 Ne4 18. Be3 a6 19. Rg1 Bxe5 20. fxe5 Qf7 21. Raf1 h5 22. c4 dxc4 23. Bxe4 Qd7 24. Bg2 b5 25. Qxh5 Nb4 26. Rd1 Nd3 27. Qe2 Rc8 28. Rgf1 Nb4 29. a3 Nd5 30. Bd2 Rfd8 31. Ba5 Re8 32. Bb4 Qf7 33. Bxd5 exd5 34. Qf3 g6 35. g4 {1-0 (34) Yu,Y (2729) -Dreev,A (2652) Doha 2016}  ) f5 {Obviously, Black doesn't have to rush with it, but I imagine it's difficult for Black to progress without it. As soon as Black plays f7-f5, preparing to reroute the black knight to e4, White can either push c3-c4, or opt for a kingside attack at the g-file.} 15. c4 {with an idea to either go forward with c4-c5 and create a passed pawn at the queenside, or take on d5, followed by Nf3-e5.} ( 16. Kh1 $5 Nf6 17. Rg1 a6 18. Ne5 Ne4 19. Rg2 {I'd like to point it out that White can ignore the knight on e4 for quite some time as it's not doing much.} Kh8 20. Rag1 Nxe5 21. fxe5 Be7 22. Rf1 $14  ) dxc4 ( Nf6 16. Rac1 Qe7 17. c5 Bc7 18. a3 $14  ) 16. Bxc4 Nb6 17. Bb3 Na5 18. Rac1 Qd7 19. Bc2 Nd5 20. Bd3 a6 21. Bf2 $14 { Despite the fact that Black has a nice outpost on d5 for his knight, his pawn on e6 is eternally weak. White seems to be pushing.}  ) ( Rfe8 13. Nf3 Nd7 14. Bd2 ( 15. Be3 $5  ) a6 15. Rae1 Na5 16. b3 $5 {a very interesting approach to stop Black's ideas at the queenside - this is why the bishop was positioned at d2.} ( 17. Ne5 Nf8 18. g4 b5 19. g5 Nc4 20. Bc1 { to me the White's attack looks very much real.}  ) b5 17. Ne5 Nf8 18. Qg2 Rad8 19. Re2 Qb6 20. Qf2 f6 21. Nf3 Nc6 22. b4 Re7 23. Kh1 Nd7 24. Qg2 Qc7 25. Rfe1 Rde8 26. Nh4 Nb6 27. Qh3 f5 28. Nf3 Nd8 29. Ne5 Nc4 30. Bc1 Nb6 31. g4 Bxe5 32. dxe5 g6 33. Be3 Na4 34. Rc2 fxg4 35. Qxg4 Rg7 36. Rg1 Nc6 37. h4 Qf7 38. Rcg2 $16 {1-0 (73) Tari,A (2595) -Arat,U (2400) Kocaeli 2017}  ) 13. Nf3 b5 { Black is eyeing for a quick b5-b4, creating some targets at the queenside.} 14. a3 {I think the rule here is as follows - if by playing a2-a3 you force Black to spend several tempos to prepare a6-a5 and b5-b4, go for it. Time is of the essence.} Ne7 15. Bd2 { a strange move but it's necessary to connect both rooks and also protect the e4 square with an additional piece. The dark-squared bishop at the moment doesn't play a critical role.} Qb7 $1 { one of the key ideas for Black - he wants to play Ne4 and strengthen it with f7-f5. I imagine that at this point it's in White's interest to stop it.} 16. Rae1 {just in time} Rab8 { one of the perks for White having the bishop on d3 and queen on e2 - it heavily slows down the b5-b4 maneuver.} 17. Ne5 { preparing to move forward with the kingside pawns.} ( 18. Ng5 Qd7 19. g4 a5 20. b4 axb4 21. axb4 h6 22. Nh3 Ne4 $1 23. Bxe4 dxe4 24. Qxe4 Rfe8 $44 {1/2-1/2 (52) Le,Q (2715) -Nisipeanu,L (2661) Batumi 2018}  ) a5 18. g4 ( 19. b4 { depending on the situation, b2-b4 is a very common idea in these lines. White stops b5-b4 from happening and fixes a weakness on b5, while the pawn on c3 is protected. However, please be advised that Black has a nice positional sacrifice at his disposal.} axb4 20. axb4 Ne4 $1 21. Bxe4 dxe4 22. Qxe4 Qxe4 23. Rxe4 Ra8 { Black has an excellent compensation for the pawn.}  ) b4 19. axb4 axb4 20. f5 $1 ( 21. g5 {would again run into the pawn sacrifice.} Ne4 $1 22. Bxe4 dxe4 23. Qxe4 Qxe4 24. Rxe4 bxc3 25. bxc3 Rfc8  ) bxc3 21. bxc3 exf5 ( Bxe5 22. Qxe5 $1 Nxg4 23. Qe2 Nf6 24. fxe6 $16  ) 22. gxf5 $14 { White's chances look better as he has an open g-file for an attack and all of his pieces are ready to join it. It would be wise to watch out for Black to play the typical Rb8-b2, causing some annoying pins.}  *

