1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6 {finally we've come to the two knights variation where Black doesn't stop White's Bf4 from being played.} 6. Bf4 ( 7. Ne2 $5 {as an element of surprise, it's possible also here to employ the same idea, explored in Chapter 5.} e5 {probably the most tempting move as White didn't stop it from happening.} ( Bg4 8. O-O e6 9. Qe1 {Comparing with the main line of Chapter 5, the biggest drawback is that Black doesn't have to "waste" a tempo on Qc7.} Bd6 ( Bh5 10. Nf4 Bg6 11. Nxg6 hxg6 12. Qe2 Bd6 13. g3 {now we've seen this position somewhere!}  ) 10. Ng3 O-O ( Nh5 11. Nf5 Bxf5 12. Bxf5 O-O 13. Bd3 Qc7 14. g3  ) 11. f3 Bh5 12. Nxh5 Nxh5 13. f4 {with the standard ideas.}  ) 8. dxe5 Nxe5 9. Bf4 Bd6 10. Bxe5 Bxe5 11. Nd2 O-O 12. Nf3 Bc7 13. O-O Bg4 14. Ned4 Ne4 15. Qc2 Re8 16. Rfe1 {should be just equal but an isolated pawn is an isolated pawn!}  ) Bg4 {Naturally, Black has to bring out his light-squared bishop to finish the development with e6 and Be7 or Bd6.} ( g6 {most likely will transform to lines in Chapter 3.}  ) 7. Qb3 {White tries to exploit the fact that the black pawn on b7 has been left unprotected. From here I will split the analysis into the remaining chapters.} e5 $5 {an interesting idea to surprise White but if you're aware of it, White gets the upper hand in the end. Perhaps the most famous game of this line is the last round of 2018 US Championship when Samuel Shankland in a stunning fashion beat Awonder Liang to take the title.} ( Na5 {for some reason is not very popular - the arising positions look very much playable to me.} 8. Qa4+ Bd7 {slightly too passive.} ( Nc6 {invitation for a draw if White plays Qb3 next - if never hurts to twice repeat the position and find out if your opponent really wants it!} 9. Nd2 {for the sake of our database, we don't want it!} e6 10. Ngf3 Bd6 11. Ne5 O-O 12. Bg3 { notice how Black can't capture on e5 because the queen from a4 attacks the bishop on g4!} Qc7 13. Nxg4 Nxg4 14. Qd1 Nf6 15. O-O { with a classic slight edge for White because of the light-squared bishop and possibilities to bother the black king at the kingside by the means of Bxd6 and f2-f4. In the particular game Black decided to solve his opening problems with a radical, yet classical solution.} Bxg3 16. hxg3 e5 17. dxe5 Nxe5 18. Nf3 {0-1 (54) Mueller, K (2545) -Agdestein, S (2545) Germany 1998. Black should be slightly suffering here, yet somehow he won the game.}  ) 9. Qc2 e6 10. Nf3 {the arising position feels like an improved Exchange Slav where the pawn on e3 has been moved to c3.} Qb6 11. a4 $1 {a powerful novelty, unleashed by Fischer some 50 years ago! The weakness of the b3 square is irrelevant as Black can't exploit it.} Rc8 12. Nbd2 Nc6 13. Qb1 Nh5 14. Be3 $1 { the dark-squared bishop is more important than the knight - by temporarily moving it to a bad square, it will come to life later. Notice how useless feels the black knight on h5.} h6 15. Ne5 Nf6 ( Nxe5 16. dxe5 Bc5 17. a5 $1 Qd8 18. Nf3 $1 g5 19. Qc1 $16 {doesn't look fun for Black as well.}  ) 16. h3 Bd6 17. O-O Kf8 $2 18. f4 Be8 19. Bf2 Qc7 20. Bh4 Ng8 21. f5 $1 $16 {1-0 (39) Fischer,R-Petrosian,T Belgrade 1970. Most likely, Black can improve the game somewhere along the way but White's gameplan seems to be quite straightforward.}  ) ( Qb6 {A relatively rare continuation. Black willingly accepts a slightly worse position but is confident that he can hold it. Whether he really can, it's up to you.} 8. Qxb6 axb6 9. Nd2 ( 10. Na3 { is very tempting but it only leads to simplifying the position.} e6 11. Nb5 Kd7  ) e6 10. Ngf3 {obviously the remaining moves are not forced and the following game is one of many. Either way, Black is slightly worse because of the doubled pawns.} Nd7 11. O-O f6 12. Rfe1 Kf7 13. a3 Bh5 14. h3 Bg6 15. Bb5 Be7 16. Re3 Rhe8 17. Rae1 Nf8 18. c4 $16 {1-0 (43) Yudasin,L (2556) -Bonin,J (2342) New York 2004}  ) ( Qc8 {analysis in Chapter 8}  ) ( Qd7 {analysis in Chapter 9}  ) 8. h3 $5