1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6 6. Bf4 Bg4 7. Qb3 Qc8 {One of the main moves which feels like a more careful approach - the other popular continuation here is 7...Qd7 which comes together with Bd6 and a potential pawn sacrifice on b7.} ( Na5 {This is an old fashioned move - Bobby Fischer beat Tigran Petrosian in this line exactly 50 years ago! There have been some attempts to revive this line.} 8. Qa4+ {forcing the bishop to go to a much more passive square.} Bd7 9. Qc2 e6 {this leads to the famous game. The choice, however, feels slightly passive.} ( Nh5 $5 { is the modern approach, as Black fights for control of the h2-b8 diagonal.} 10. Be3 Qc7 { Black intends to play Nf4 real soon.} ( g6 11. Nf3 Bg7 12. Nbd2 O-O 13. O-O { here the late Qc7 and Nh5-f4 can be met with Rfe1 and Bd3-f1 with ideas to play Nf3-e5.} f5 {trying to justify the knight's placement on h5, but this weakens the e5 square forever.} 14. Nb3 Nc4 15. Qe2 Nxe3 16. Qxe3 b6 17. Rfe1 e6 18. Ne5 Ba4 19. Nd2 Qe7 20. Ndf3 $14 {1/2-1/2 (24) Novikov,M (2510) -Gusev,A (2411) Bogoroditsk 2011}  ) 11. Nf3 Nc6 ( Nf4 $6 {would be a too hasty decision.} 12. Bxf4 Qxf4 13. Ne5  ) 12. O-O Nf4 13. Bxf4 Qxf4 14. Re1 e6 15. Nbd2 Bd6 16. Nb3 { White feels a little better because of the control of the central squares, but it's not much.}  ) ( a6 { with the same idea to exchange the light-squared bishops but here it would double the b-pawns. White has a pleasant choice.} 10. Nd2 ( 11. a4 $5 Bg4 { Black does trade the bishops after all, but it costs him quite a few tempos. Thus White should have at least an edge.} 12. Nd2 Bh5 13. Ngf3 Bg6 14. Ne5 e6 15. O-O Bd6 16. Rfe1 O-O 17. Nxg6 hxg6 18. Be5 Bxe5 19. dxe5 Nd7 20. b4 Nc6 21. Nf3 Rc8 22. Qe2 Ne7 23. Rac1 Nf5 24. a5 Qe7 25. g3 Rc7 26. Kg2 Rfc8 27. Qd2 Nb8 28. h4 $14 {0-1 (42) Campora,D (2540) -Tukmakov,V (2590) Biel 1988}  ) e6 11. Ngf3 Bb5 12. Bxb5+ axb5 {Now Black has got what he wanted but White's game is very easy and Black is struggling to find a game plan or some targets.} 13. a3 Be7 14. O-O O-O 15. Rae1 Nc4 16. Ne5 Ra6 17. Nd3 Rc6 18. Qd1 Rb6 19. Nf3 Ne4 20. Nfe5 Bf6 21. f3 Ned6 22. Ng4 Bh4 23. g3 Bg5 24. Bxd6 Nxd6 25. h4 Be7 26. h5 {Essentially White has a free attack at the kingside while Black has to sit and wait. 1-0 (82) Aronian, L (2765) -Karjakin, S (2753) Kolkata 2018}  ) 10. Nf3 {feels like an improved Exchange Slav.} Qb6 { Black is threatening to exchange the light-squared bishops} 11. a4 $1 Rc8 ( Qb3 12. Qe2  ) 12. Nbd2 Nc6 13. Qb1 Nh5 14. Be3 h6 15. Ne5 Nf6 16. h3 Bd6 17. O-O Kf8 $2 18. f4 Be8 19. Bf2 Qc7 20. Bh4 Ng8 21. f5 $16 {1-0 (39) Fischer,R-Petrosian, T Belgrade 1970}  ) 8. Nd2 { Preparing to play Ngf3. Because of the need to protect the b7 pawn the f5 square is out of bounds so in order to trade the light-squared bishop Black is going to play Bh5-g6 at some moment. The question is - which is the right moment? There are quite subtle nuances.} e6 ( Bh5 9. Ngf3 Bg6 {this is probably the earliest attempt and this gives White an interesting opportunity.} 10. Bb5 $5 { with a very simple threat of Nf3-e5 and Qa4. This idea might be possible in various order of the moves, should Black rush with Bh5-g6.} a6 11. Bxc6+ {now Black is at crossroads - it pretty much doesn't matter with what he will take as White's approach will be the same, to push c3-c4.} bxc6 ( Qxc6 12. a4 $1 {it's quite important to take away the b5 square before pushing c3-c4 to avoid a queen trade.} e6 13. Ne5 Qc8 14. O-O Be7 15. Rac1 O-O 16. c4 $14 { and things look really unpleasant for Black, mostly because of the weak b6 square and the pawn on b7 feels quite vulnerable.}  ) 12. Qa4 Nd7 13. O-O e6 14. c4 Nb6 ( Bd3 $2 15. Rfc1 Qb7 ( Nb6 $4 16. Qb3 { going for the c4 pawn doesn't work for Black as he simply drops a piece}  ) 16. cxd5 cxd5 17. Rc7 Qb5 18. Qxb5 Bxb5 19. a4 Be2 20. Re1 Bxf3 21. Nxf3 $16  ) 15. Qa5 Nxc4 16. Nxc4 dxc4 17. Ne5 Qb7 18. Nxc4 { and because of the weakness on c6 Black is suffering.} Bb4 19. Qb6 Qxb6 20. Nxb6 Rd8 21. Rfd1 Bd6 22. Bxd6 Rxd6 23. Rac1 Ke7 24. Nc4 Rd5 25. Ne5 f6 26. Nxg6+ hxg6 27. Rxc6 $14 {1-0 (50) Pospisil,L (2489) -Deskin,G (2160) ICCF email 2016}  ) 9. Ngf3 Be7 ( Bh5 {one more attempt to land the bishop on g6 early.} 10. O-O Bg6 ( Be7 11. Rae1 {will transpose to the main line}  ) 11. Bb5 $5 {also here it should work!} a6 ( Be7 {if Black doesn't play a7-a6, he has to give up his light-squared bishop for a knight.} 12. Ne5 O-O 13. Nxg6 hxg6 14. Bd3 { and we're back to the traditional plan - Nf3, g2-g3, Kg1-g2, h2-h4, Rf1-h1 and prepare h4-h5.}  ) 12. Bxc6+ bxc6 ( Qxc6 13. a4 Bd6 14. Bxd6 Qxd6 15. c4 O-O 16. c5 Qc7 17. Rfc1 {White feels better.}  ) 13. Qa4 ( 14. c4 Nh5 15. Be5 f6 16. cxd5 exd5 ( fxe5 $5  ) 17. Rfe1 Kf7 18. Rac1 Kg8 19. Bg3 Nxg3 20. hxg3 Qd7 21. Qa4 Be8 22. Qc2 Bd6 23. Nb3 a5 24. Nc5 Bxc5 25. Qxc5 Kf7 26. Re3 a4 27. Rce1 Ra7 28. Ra3 Qb7 29. b3 Rf8 30. bxa4 Kg8 31. Rae3 Ra8 32. Rb3 Qa7 33. Qxa7 Rxa7 34. Rb4 Bd7 35. Nd2 c5 36. dxc5 Bxa4 37. Nf3 Bc2 38. Nd4 Rxa2 39. Rb7 Ba4 40. Ree7 Ra1+ 41. Kh2 {1-0 (40) Stojanovski,D (2429) -Camber,I (1948) Rijeka 2008}  ) Nh5 ( Nd7 14. c4 {transforms to a line, covered earlier.}  ) 14. Be3 Bd6 15. Ne5 O-O 16. Qxc6 ( 17. c4 $5  ) Bxe5 17. Qxc8 Bxh2+ 18. Kxh2 Rfxc8 19. Nb3 Rab8 20. Bc1 Nf6 21. Nc5 $14  ) ( Bxf3 10. Nxf3 $14 { gives White immediately a solid advantage and chances to build an attack at the kingside.}  ) 10. O-O Bh5 {probably this is the best moment when Black could reroute the bishop to g6, and this is why it's quite popular at the top level.} ( O-O 11. Qc2 $1 {and now it's slightly too late for Black to reroute the bishop on g6 as White will keep his light-squared bishop!} Bh5 ( Bf5 {engines think that this is a playable move and they might be right. But from a human's perspective Black has ruined his pawn structure and almost any endgame should be in White's favour.} 12. Bxf5 exf5 13. Rfe1  ) 12. Ne5 a6 {obviously, Black can't take on e5 as after dxe5 he loses a pawn on h7.} 13. Rae1 Bg6 {this is not mandatory and it's entirely possible that Black can postpone this decision and start with b7-b5 and focus at the queenside first, but he will have to do this sooner or later.} ( b5 14. Re3  ) 14. Nxg6 hxg6 15. Nf3 {with a very simple plan at the kingside.} b5 16. a3 Ra7 17. Qe2 Re8 18. h4 Bd8 19. g3 Ne7 20. Kg2 Nf5 21. Rh1 Bc7 22. Ne5 Bb8 23. g4 Nd6 24. h5 {With a winning attack. Seemingly Black made normal looking moves - can you clearly pinpoint his mistake? 1-0 (36) Berkes,F (2661) -McShane,L (2647) Heraklio 2017}  ) 11. Rae1 {The bishop trade is going to happen so White concentrates all his forces at the kingside.} ( 12. Ne5 Nxe5 $1 ( O-O 13. Qc2 {would transform to a favourable line where Black most likely will have to give up his light-squared bishop for a knight.}  ) 13. Bxe5 O-O 14. c4 $5 dxc4 15. Nxc4 Bg6 16. Bxg6 hxg6 17. Rac1 Qd7 18. Na5 b6 19. Rc7 Qe8 20. Nc6 Bd8 21. Nxd8 Qxd8 22. Qa4 Nd5 23. Rxa7 Rxa7 24. Qxa7 Qa8 25. Qxa8 Rxa8 26. a3 Rc8 27. h4 f6 28. Bg3 Rc2 $44 {1/2-1/2 (27) Sedlak,N (2559) -Gledura,B (2414) Hungary 2015}  ) ( 12. Rfe1 Bg6 13. Bb5 {specifically here this doesn't look so great as Black can both castle and avoid playing early a7-a6.} O-O {Taking on c6 is not so appealing anymore if Black doesn't play a6 and weaken his b6 square.} 14. Ne5 Nxe5 15. Bxe5 a6 16. Be2 Nd7 $11  ) Bg6 {For Black it's better to trade the bishop before castling} ( O-O {Black can also postpone the bishop's rerouting to g6 but practice proves that this is a dangerous idea - White's attack becomes quite obvious.} 12. Qc2 {Still intending to play Nf3-e5, if allowed, transposing to some of the covered lines.} ( 13. g3 $5 $146 { for the sake of simplicity White can stick to his original plan and continue with Kg1-g2, h2-h4 and at some point - Ne5. Black will have to play Bg6 at some point anyway, so the position will transpose to one of the main lines.}  ) Bg6 13. Bxg6 hxg6 14. Qd3 { keeping an eye on b7-b5 and preparing to reroute the queen to h3.} a6 15. Ng5 Nh5 16. Qh3 Re8 ( Bxg5 17. Bxg5 Re8 18. f4 $146 ( 19. Qh4 e5 20. dxe5 Nxe5 21. h3 Qc6 22. Qd4 Nd7 23. Be7 Nhf6 24. Re3 Nf8 25. Bxf6 gxf6 26. Rfe1 Rxe3 27. Rxe3 Kg7 28. Nf1 Ne6 29. Qd2 Nc5 30. Ng3 Ne4 31. Qd4 Re8 32. Ne2 Ng5 33. Nf4 Re4 34. Rxe4 dxe4 35. Nd5 Qe6 36. c4 Qf5 37. Qb6 Nxh3+ 38. gxh3 {1-0 (37) Gabuzyan,H (2613) -Sorokin,A (2531) Chicago 2019}  )  ) 17. Ndf3 b5 18. Bc1 Bxg5 19. Bxg5 f6 20. g4 $1 $146 ( 21. Be3 $6 e5 22. g4 exd4 23. Nxd4 Ne5 24. f3 Nd3 25. Qh4 Nhf4 26. Bxf4 Nxe1 27. Rxe1 g5 28. Rxe8+ Qxe8 29. Bxg5 fxg5 30. Qxg5 $11 {1-0 (116) Melkumyan,H (2660) -Belenkaya, D (2357) Caleta 2019}  ) e5 21. Qg2 fxg5 22. gxh5 $16  ) 12. Bxg6 hxg6 {Black is very solid but actually because of the doubled pawns, White can think about a future attack at the kingside, linked with h2-h4-h5.} 13. g3 $5 { First played by Jan Krzysztof Duda last year - I like this move the most. White is going to play g2-g3 anyway as it fits the concept so why not play it immediately? The idea remains the same - play h2-h4, Kg2, Rh1 and aim for a kingside attack once Black will short castle.} ( 14. h4 $5 { was first played by Vladimir Kramnik in his World Cup match against Vasyl Ivanchuk back in 2017. The idea is not to waste time and prepare for a kingside attack with the following g2-g3, Kg2 and Rh1, should Black make a short castle.} a6 15. c4 ( 16. a4 Nh5 17. Bh2 Nf6 {Instead of the repetition, it's difficult to come up here with a move for White! I am pretty sure that Carlsen went here deliberately as draw secured him a win in the mini-match.} 18. Bf4 Nh5 19. Bh2 Nf6 20. Bf4 {½-½ (18) Carlsen,M (2863) -So,W (2770) Lindores Abbey 2020}  ) a5 16. a3 a4 17. Qd3 O-O 18. c5 b6 19. cxb6 Qb7 20. Bc7 Nd7 {0-1 (71) Kramnik,V (2803) -Ivanchuk,V (2728) Tbilisi 2017}  ) O-O {the most logical move although maybe Black can postpone castling for some time and focus on queenside activities first.} ( a6 14. h4 b5 15. Kg2 ( 16. a3 Kf8 17. Kg2 Nh5 18. Bg5 Bd6 19. Ne5 Qc7 $2 20. Ndf3 ( 21. Nxg6+ $1 fxg6 22. Rxe6  ) Re8 21. Qd1 Nf6 22. Nxc6 Qxc6 23. Bxf6 gxf6 24. Re2 a5 25. Qd3 Qc4 26. Ne1 Rb8 27. Rc2 Kg7 28. Rh1 Rbc8 29. Qe3 Qb3 30. Qf3 Qa4 31. h5 Rxh5 32. Rxh5 gxh5 33. Qxh5 b4 34. axb4 axb4 35. Qe2 bxc3 36. bxc3 Qc4 {1/2-1/2 (35) Kopinits,A (2209) -Cvitan,E (2289) Austria 2020}  ) Qb7 16. Rh1 { and the question is - for how long can the black king remain in the centre? Objectively the position remains equal.}  ) ( Nh5 14. Be3 ( {the immediate} 15. Bg5 {can run into some hostilities after} f6 16. Be3 g5 $13  ) O-O 15. Kg2 Nf6 16. Bg5 a6 17. h4  ) 14. Kg2 $146 {Technically a novelty, but the idea remains the same.} ( 15. Ne5 {Duda played this in the game. I can only assume he was somewhat concerned about the potential Nf6-h5 idea and wasn't too fond of the option to trade the dark-squared bishops. Thus he removed the idea for good and forced the other black knight to retreat to d7. However, here White's attack feels slightly unprepared and gives Black plenty of chances to organize a counter-attack at the queenside.} Nxe5 16. dxe5 Nd7 17. h4 Nc5 18. Qc2 Qc6 19. Re3 Qa6 20. Qb1 Rac8 21. Kg2 b5 22. Bg5 Qb7 23. Bxe7 Qxe7 24. Rh1 a5 25. Qd1 b4 26. Qg4 bxc3 27. bxc3 Rb8 28. h5 g5 29. h6 g6 30. Nf3 Ne4 $11 {0-1 (50) Duda,J (2738) -Van Foreest,J (2612) Wijk aan Zee 2019}  ) a6 15. h4 b5 16. Ne5 {from here the following lines are not forced and they merely illustrate the idea how the game might continue.} Qb7 17. Rh1 Nh5 ( Nxe5 18. dxe5 {I think it's important to aim for the position where White can capture on e5 with a pawn, otherwise pushing h4-h5 doesn't look too real.} Nh5 19. Bg5 d4+ 20. Ne4 dxc3 21. Qxc3  ) ( a5 18. Bg5 a4 ( b4 19. Qc2 Rfc8 20. Qd3  ) 19. Qc2 b4 ( a3 20. Bxf6 Bxf6 21. Ng4 Rfc8 22. Nf3 axb2 23. h5 Ne7 24. hxg6 Nxg6 25. Rxe6 $1 $40  ) 20. Bxf6 gxf6 ( Bxf6 21. Ng4  ) 21. Nxg6 fxg6 22. Qxg6+ Kh8 23. Nf3 $40  ) 18. Bg5 Rae8 ( f6 $4 19. Nxg6 fxg5 20. Rxe6 {and Black's position falls apart.}  ) 19. Qc2 b4 20. Ndf3 { the black knight can't stay on h5 forever as it will be pushed out, thus h4-h5 should happen in a near future. I like White's chances.}  *

