1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6 6. Bf4 Bg4 7. Qb3 Qd7 { the most ambitious move - Black is not afraid of any early Nf3-e5 ideas and wants to trade the dark-squared bishops with Bd6, even if it costs him a pawn on b7.} 8. Nd2 e6 9. Ngf3 {White's plan doesn't change, whether the black queen is on c8 or d7 - focus on the game at the kingside as this is where the black king will be.} Bd6 {I think the best approach for Black is to keep his light-squared bishop.} ( Bxf3 {It is my understanding that early giving up the light-squared bishop on f3 makes White's life a little easier, with some extra options. The bishop on d3 does a wonderful job attacking the kingside and also keeping an eye on the queenside.} 10. Nxf3 Bd6 11. Bg3 $1 { If Black has traded his light-squared bishop, White doesn't have to give up the control of the e5 square.} ( 12. Bxd6 {is the other reasonable alternative which will feel quite similar to the main lines.} Qxd6 13. O-O O-O ( Rb8 14. a4 ( 15. Rae1 O-O  ) O-O 15. Rfe1 Nd7 16. a5 h6 17. Qa3 Qxa3 18. Rxa3 Rfc8 {1-0 (52) Jumabayev,R (2612) -Saric,I (2669) Riadh 2017}  ) 14. Rae1 {will transform into one of the main lines of this chapter.} ( 15. Qxb7 Rab8 16. Qa6 Rb6 17. Qa3 Qxa3 18. bxa3 Rc8 19. Rab1 Na5 $44  )  ) O-O 12. O-O Bxg3 13. hxg3 Qc7 14. Rfe1 Rab8 ( Nd7 $5 $146 15. Qc2 h6 16. Qd2 a6 17. g4 $14 { I have a feeling that Black will have to push e6-e5 and try to hold a slightly worse position, otherwise White's attack looks quite dangerous.}  ) 15. Qc2 b5 16. a3 a5 17. Ne5 {1/2-1/2 (17) Smirin,I (2615) -Khalifman,A (2645) Elenite 1994} ( 18. Qe2 $5 b4 19. cxb4 axb4 20. a4 $14  )  ) 10. Bxd6 ( {here} 11. Bg3 {doesn't look so interesting as Black still has the light-squared bishop which can be rerouted to h5.} Bh5  ) ( 11. Ne5 {is tempting but gives nothing. Doesn't mean it's unplayable!} Qc7 12. Nxg4 Bxf4 13. Nxf6+ gxf6 14. Nf3 $11  ) Qxd6 11. O-O O-O {I believe all of this is more or less forced and this is where White has to make a choice.} ( Bh5 $6 12. Qxb7 {if Black wants to make everything out of the opening, he has to make sure that White can't really take the pawn on b7. Here, it seems, it's simply a free pawn.} Rb8 13. Qa6 Rb6 14. Qa4 $16 {and Black is not in time to grab back the pawn on b2.}  ) 12. Rae1 { This is the move that I like the most - White doesn't hide his plan to play at the kingside with the traditional ideas of Nf3-e5, Re3-h3 and probably f2-f4. Plus, it's the same rook manoeuvre as in Chapter 8. Let us stop here for a moment as Black is at the crossroads. As far as I can see, these are his options: 1) Continue with the traditional plan and reroute the bishop on g6. However, with the short castle already done, Black has to understand that there might be a quick and annoying attack at the h-file. 2) Play Nd7 to stop White from playing Nf3-e5 and f2-f4. This allows White almost by force to exchange Black's light-squared bishop and create some targets at the kingside. 3) Black can trade on f3 right away and focus at the queenside. By doing so he wouldn't have to worry about a quick attack at the h-file (had the bishop been rerouted to g6 and traded there) but this gives White quite a lot of freedom. 4) Ignore White's ideas, keep the bishop on g4 as long as it takes and focus on his own ideas at the queenside. Not surprisingly, the last two ideas at the moment are the most popular choices.} ( 13. Rfe1 {might be a more modest alternative, keeping the other rook at the queenside for the time being, as a2-a4 might be an option at some point.} Rab8 ( Nd7 14. Qc2 {A nice trick to force Black to exchange his light-squared bishop.} h6 15. h3 Bxf3 ( Bh5 $6 16. g4  ) 16. Nxf3 $14  ) 14. Ne5 Bh5 15. a4 a6 16. a5 {however, by doing this White should understand that he won't have the time to play on both kingside and queenside, thus an attack against the king looks unlikely to happen.}  ) Rab8 {Black completely ignores what's happening at the kingside and focuses instead on making b7-b5-b4 to happen as quickly as possible. This also gives him some room for improvisation, for example, at the right time to reroute the bishop to g6.} ( Nd7 13. Qc2 h6 {the most played move in the position, however, I do think that the lesser-played alternative is better.} ( g6 $1 14. Re3 {It's quite difficult to prove that White has here anything at all. I suggest the text move, preparing against Bf5 by either doubling the rooks at the e-file, or transfer one of them to h3, and would avoid playing h2-h3, if possible.} Bf5 15. Bxf5 gxf5 ( exf5 16. Rfe1  ) 16. Ng5  ) 14. h3 Bxf3 ( Bh5 $6 15. g4  ) 15. Nxf3 { with a lot of manoeuvring at the kingside. Black will continue with his traditional b7-b5-b4 plan.}  ) ( Bxf3 {One of the most popular continuations but this gives White quite a lot of freedom to improvise at the kingside.} 13. Nxf3 Qc7 14. Qc2 { the queen has nothing to do at the queenside anymore and should be rerouted closer to the kingside. White is threatening to play Ne5 and Black should do something about it, otherwise, the follow-up after that will be f2-f4.} g6 ( Rac8 15. Qe2 a6 16. g3 b5 17. a3 Rfe8 18. Kg2 Rb8 19. h4 h6 20. Rh1 Nd7 21. Bb1 a5 22. Qd3 Nf8 23. b4 Rec8 24. Re3 Rb7 25. Rhe1 Qb6 26. Nd2 a4 27. Nf3 Rbc7 28. Qd2 Qb8 29. h5 Rb7 30. Nh2 Qd6 31. Ng4 $14 {0-1 (51) Kovalev,V (2636) -Riazantsev,A (2666) Sochi 2017}  ) ( h6 15. g3 { and so on.}  ) 15. Qd2 Kg7 16. Ne5 $5 {a rare move in this particular position, a long time ago played by then young Hikaru Nakamura - I don't think everything is clear here as it looks interesting.} ( 17. Re3 Rab8 18. a4 a6 19. Rfe1 Qf4 20. Qd1 b5 21. axb5 axb5 22. b4 Rfc8 23. h3 Qc7 24. Nd2 Ne7 25. Bc2 Nf5 26. Bxf5 gxf5 27. Nb3 Ne4 28. Nc5 $11 {0-1 (61) Ter Sahakyan,S (2563) -Swapnil,S (2533) chess.com INT 2018}  ) Nxe5 17. dxe5 Nd7 18. Qf4 Kg8 19. h4 $5 $146 ( 20. Qg5 Qd8 21. Qh6 { 1/2-1/2 (20) Nakamura,H (2452) -Doettling,F (2518) Boston 2001}  ) f6 20. h5 Nxe5 21. hxg6 hxg6 22. Bxg6 Kg7 23. Qg3 $14  ) ( Bh5 13. Ne5 Qc7 14. f4 Bg6 15. Bxg6 $1 { I think it's important to keep the knight on e5 - the bishop has done its job and thus it's alright to trade it.} hxg6 16. Re3 { it can be quite problematic to come up with a proper defense against the simple White's plan.} Qb6 {perhaps already a necessity.} ( Ne7 17. Rh3 Nf5 18. g4 Nd6 19. Qd1 Nfe4 20. Nxe4 Nxe4 21. Qe1 Qe7 22. g5 { is a sample line of how quickly can Black get checkmated.}  ) 17. Qxb6 axb6 18. a3 {with a long and manoeuvring game. Notice that Black pawns are quite static thus I imagine that only White can make a progress by carefully advancing the pawns at the kingside. Once the black knight will land on c4, it should be ignored and the white knight on d3 keeps everything protected.}  ) ( Ne7 $5 { In the Chessable course "Lifetime Repertoires: Caro Kann" the Dutch GM Erwin L'Ami gives the following continuation for Black as a recommendation - Black is threatening with the immediate Bg4-f5 and not spoiling his pawn structure. It seems that there's nothing that White can do about it but treat it this way - Black loses a lot of tempos in the process and White gains a considerable space advantage at the kingside. If Black will play it out perfectly, probably he will manage to equalize in the end, however, it is White who is constantly pushing Black and not the other way around.} 13. Ne5 Bf5 14. Bxf5 Nxf5 15. g4 {it's time to grab some additional space advantage!} ( 16. Qxb7 {is not really impressive here as after} Rab8 17. Qxa7 Rxb2 18. Nb3 Qe7 $1 { Black has plenty of compensation for the sacrificed pawn. For example,} 19. Qa5 Ne4 20. c4 Qb7 21. Nd3 ( 22. Qa3 Rc2 23. Rc1 Re2  ) Rc2 22. cxd5 Ra8 23. Qb4 Qxd5 24. Nf4 Qc6 25. Rc1 h6 $11  ) Ne7 ( Nh4 {is also possible but most likely it will be rerouted to g6 and after that - to e7 anyway.} 16. f4  ) 16. Qb5 $146 { My suggested improvement, which is also similar to what Kotronias did in the only game in this line - the queen is immediately transferred to either d3 or e2, while f2-f4 can wait for the moment. Black can't play b7-b5 just yet.} ( 17. f4 b5 $1 $146 {Llami's suggested continuation which looks quite strong as Black is not wasting time for the preparation moves a6 and Rb8.} ( Rab8 18. Qb5 a6 19. Qd3 b5 20. f5 ( 21. a3 a5 22. f5 exf5 23. gxf5 b4 24. cxb4 axb4 25. a4 Ra8 26. Re2 Rxa4 27. Rg2 Ra7 28. Qg3 g6 29. fxg6 fxg6 30. Rgf2 Raa8 31. Qg5 Ne4 32. Nxe4 dxe4 33. Nf7 Qe6 34. Nh6+ Kg7 35. Rf7+ Rxf7 36. Rxf7+ Qxf7 37. Nxf7 Kxf7 38. Qf4+ {1-0 (65) Kotronias,V (2505) -Olsen,F (2354) Aarhus 2018}  ) exf5 21. gxf5 b4 22. Re2 $36  ) 18. g5 ( 19. f5 {unfortunately doesn't give the desired results} exf5 20. gxf5 Rab8 21. Re2 b4 22. Rg2 Nc6 $1 23. Nxc6 Qxc6 24. cxb4 Qb6 25. Qe3 Rfe8 $11  ) Ne8 {however, starting from here the game is not forced. Probably the pawn on b5 is untouchable due to the typical Rb8-Rxb2 but White has a potential to increase the pressure at the kingside where he enjoys a solid space advantage.} ( Nh5 $5 19. Qxb5 Ng6 20. Qe2 ( 21. f5 Ngf4 22. Qd7 Qb6 $13  ) Ngxf4 ( Nhxf4 $6 21. Qe3 Nh5 22. Nxg6 hxg6 23. Nf3 $16  ) 21. Qe3 f6 22. gxf6 gxf6 23. Nd3 Nxd3 24. Qxd3 Kh8 25. Kh1 Rab8 26. Nb3 e5 27. Qh3 Nf4 28. Qf5 Ng6 $11  ) 19. Rf3 Nf5 20. Qd1 Qe7 21. Qe2 ( 22. Rh3 f6 23. Qh5 g6 {there is no mate.}  ) b4 22. Nb3 bxc3 23. bxc3 Ned6 24. Nc5 Nb7 25. Nxb7 Qxb7 26. Rh3 f6 27. gxf6 Rxf6 28. Kh1 $11  ) a6 ( Qc7 $5 {this might be a smart approach to wait for White to play f2-f4 first so that Black can gain control of the e4 square.} 17. Qe2 {there's no need to rush with the f-pawn first. At times playing out this variation can feel like playing cat and mouse.} ( 18. f4 Nc8 19. g5 Nd6 20. Qe2 Nfe4 21. Nxe4 Nxe4 $11  ) Nc8 18. g5 Nd7 19. f4 Nd6 20. Rf3 g6 ( Nxe5 21. fxe5 Nf5 22. Nf1  ) 21. Rh3 Rae8 22. Kh1 {and all eyes are what's happening at the kingside. Black's counterplay at the queenside is both late and irrelevant at the moment. Black still looks too solid to break through immediately.}  ) 17. Qd3 ( 18. Qe2 b5 19. Nd3 { also looks fairly interesting, with the knight on d3 controlling many critical squares around, including b4 and c5, so that White can focus on the kingside.}  ) b5 {if Black follows the traditional approach and organizes a counter-attack at the queenside, White should be a little faster.} ( Ne8 $5 {being ready to meet f2-f4 with f7-f6.} 18. Qh3 Qc7 19. f4 Nd6 20. Rf3 { and White is either blatantly attacking with a checkmate threat on h7, or provoking weaknesses from Black. Engines always evaluate it cooly and announce equality.}  ) 18. f4 b4 19. f5 exf5 20. gxf5 bxc3 21. bxc3 Rac8 22. Qh3 Rc7 23. Re3 Rfc8 24. Rg3 $40 { you'll notice this motif to appear more than once - that's a nice idea to know.}  ) 13. Ne5 b5 { a thematic approach but this does weaken the c5 square - I suggest to try to exploit it.} 14. a3 {stopping the immediate b5-b4 and there's no need for a flashy queen's sacrifice!} ( 15. Bxb5 $5 a6 16. Bxc6 Rxb3 17. axb3 {this is definitely interesting but I feel that only White can get in trouble here.} Bf5 18. b4 Ng4 19. Ba4 h5 20. h3 Nxe5 21. Rxe5 f6 22. Re3 e5 23. Nb3 Bc2 24. Ra1 h4 25. Nc5 Bxa4 26. Rxa4 exd4 27. cxd4 Qb6 28. b3 Ra8 29. Re7 Qd6 30. Rd7 Qc6 31. Rb7 Qd6 32. Rd7 Qc6 33. Rb7 Qe8 34. Ra1 Rb8 35. Rd7 Rd8 36. Rb7 Rb8 37. Rd7 Rd8 38. Rb7 {1/2-1/2 (37) Aronian,L (2767) -Mamedyarov,S (2801) Saint Louis 2018}  ) Rfc8 {Black stops Qc2 from happening.} ( a5 15. Bxb5 Na7 16. a4 $14 {is the key difference, why a2-a3 was so important to include.}  ) ( Bh5 {better later than never, at least for some clarity.} 15. Qc2 $1 $146 { I believe that White can get an advantage out of this position as Nb3 is an incoming threat.} a5 16. Nb3 { threatening also with a simple pawn grab!} a4 ( b4 $4 {Black has no time to play this} 17. Nxc6 Qxc6 18. Nxa5 $18  ) 17. Nc1 Bg6 18. Bxg6 hxg6 19. Ncd3 $16 { White returns to the simple plan. As Aleksandrs Koblencs once said about his famous student Mikhail Tal: "If Misha has an open file, there will be a checkmate".}  ) 15. Re3 ( 16. Qa2 $5 $146 {Since the c2 square is not available because of the Nxd4 threat, there is another way to free up the b3 square for the knight!} a5 17. Nb3 a4 18. Na1 $5 { I would pick here White without thinking.}  ) Bh5 16. Rfe1 {and White is keeping tabs on a7-a5, being ready to respond with Bxb5 and a3-a4. The engines say that the position is about equal but it really depends if Black can push a7-a5 and b5-b4.} a5 17. Bxb5 Na7 18. a4 Qb6 19. f3 $1 Nxb5 20. axb5 Qxb5 21. Qxb5 Rxb5 22. b3 $14 { We've seen the arising idea already from another line - the black bishop feels a little useless at h5. I won't pretend and announce that White gains an advantage in the main lines. I think they are interesting, relatively unexplored and with the ideas, presented in the database, you should have more chances than your opponent, especially if he's unprepared. Happy hunting!}  *

