1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nf6 5. c3 Bg4 $5 {in the past few years this continuation has had some extra popularity so I decided to include this in my database as a separate chapter. I wasn't always able to find how to transform the arising positions to already covered lines, so I had to dig a little deeper.} ( Nc6 6. Bf4 {transforms to chapters 6-9.}  ) 6. Qb3 { I suggest following the same approach as in Chapters 6-9. Since the pawn on b7 at the moment is unprotected, we can try to win a tempo.} ( 7. Nf3 { of course, White can always just play normal developing moves but by doing so Black is facing no problems in the opening as the light-squared bishop is quickly rerouted to g6.}  ) ( 7. Ne2 {This is playable but the problem is that Black has saved up a tempo for Qc7 which I covered in Chapter 5. Thus I wouldn't want to recommend something that is lesser than in another chapter.} Nc6 8. O-O e6  ) Qc7 {in my eyes, the only critical move - other continuations don't really pose a problem.} ( Qb6 $6 {Black voluntarily accepts a slightly worse position.} 7. Qxb6 axb6 8. Na3 e6 ( Na6 9. Nb5 e6 10. Bf4 Be7 11. Ne2 Bxe2 12. Kxe2 $14 {1-0 (54) Kobalia,M (2614) -Kuzubov,Y (2643) chess.com INT 2020}  ) 9. Nb5 Kd7 10. Ne2 $14  ) ( Qc8 $6 {there have been some attempts to play this move, but I don't really understand it. White can proceed with the same h2-h3 idea and if Black would be willing to sacrifice a pawn on d5, the queen on c8 seems to be simply misplaced.} 7. h3 ( 8. Bf4 Nc6 9. Nd2 e6 10. Ngf3 {would transform to the Chapter 8, but I think the new line is better.}  ) Bd7 ( Bf5 $2 8. Bxf5 Qxf5 9. Qxb7  ) ( Bh5 8. g4 $1 $146 {to my great surprise, this is an actual novelty! After 6...Qc7 this is the critical move with an unclear position.} ( 9. Bf4 Nc6 10. Nd2 e6 11. Ngf3 Be7 12. O-O O-O 13. Rfe1 Bg6 14. Bxg6 hxg6 15. Ne5 Nxe5 16. Bxe5 Qc6 17. a4 Bd6 18. Nf3 Nd7 19. Bxd6 Qxd6 20. Re3 Rab8 21. Ne1 Nf6 22. Nd3 Ne4 23. Rae1 Qc7 24. Qd1 a6 25. h4 $14 {0-1 (41) Eljanov, P (2672) -Hakobyan, A (2588) Lichess.org INT 2020}  ) Bg6 9. Bxg6 hxg6 10. g5 Nfd7 {Black can never give any intermezzo checks on e6 as the pawn on b7 will be left undefended, and the rook as well.} 11. Qxd5 $16 {I cannot imagine how Qc8 is better than Qc7 in this line.}  ) 8. Bf4 Nc6 9. Nd2 $14 {and Black is never going to be able to play Bf5 and Qxf5 as the pawn on b7 is under attack.}  ) ( Qd7 7. Bf4 Nc6 8. Nd2 e6 9. Ngf3 {would transform to Chapter 9.}  ) 7. h3 {I wasn't able to find any other moves that could pose problems for Black so I treat this move as the most critical continuation.} ( 8. g3 $6 $146 { I've tried to play this in several online blitz games myself, and although I was never punished, it's a risky move if Black is up to the task.} Nc6 9. Bf4 e5 $1 10. dxe5 Nxe5 ( g5 $5 {engines love this move.}  ) 11. Bb5+ Nfd7 12. Nd2 O-O-O {Black simply looks better because of the weakened white king.}  ) ( 8. Ne2 {This is an alternative but I'm not satisfied that I'd have to mix together two ideas - Qb3 and Ne2. As you already read in Chapters 4-6, the White queen would typically go to e1.} Nc6 9. Bf4 Qd7 10. O-O e6 11. Bg3 Be7 12. h3 Bf5 13. Bxf5 exf5 14. Nf4 O-O 15. Bh4 Rad8 16. Bxf6 Bxf6 17. Nd3 Na5 18. Qc2 Nc4 19. Nd2 Rfe8 20. Rfe1 b6 21. Rad1 g6 $11 {1-0 (46) Praggnanandhaa, R (2536) -Wei, Y (2736) chess.com INT 2019}  ) Bd7 {If Black takes the peaceful approach, we've managed to win a tempo by driving away the bishop from a possible rerouting to g6 and can proceed with a positional game.} ( Bh5 $5 {Black accepts the challenge!} 8. g4 {the moment of truth - either it works, or it doesn't! This is the start of a forced sequence after which White wins a pawn by force.} Bg6 9. Bxg6 hxg6 10. g5 Nfd7 ( Nh5 $6 {the knight looks stuck here and is not contributing much to Black's compensation for the pawn.} 11. Qxd5 Nc6 12. Nf3 e6 13. Qe4 Bd6 14. Be3 Ne7 15. Nbd2 Nf5 16. O-O-O O-O 17. Kb1 $16 {1-0 (52) Abdusattorov,N (2627) -Sadhwani,R (2545) Lichess.org 