redibly complex and the engines insist that this is a draw...} Kxh7 17. Ng5+ Kg6 ( Kh6 18. Ndf3 Nf4 19. Qe3 g6 20. g3 Kg7 21. gxf4 Rae8 $13  ) 18. Ndf3 Nf4 19. Qc2+ Kf6 20. g3 Ng6 21. Nxf7 Kxf7 22. Ng5+ Kg8 23. Qxg6 Nf6 24. Nxe6 Qd7 25. Bh6 Ne4 26. Rxe4 dxe4 27. Ng5 Rf7 28. Qh7+ ( 29. Nxf7 Qxf7 30. Qxd6 gxh6 31. Qxh6 Rf8 32. Qg5+ {and probably the game would end with a perpetual check unless Black wants to play with a bishop against 4 white pawns.}  ) Kf8 29. Nxf7 Qxf7 30. d5 Qxd5 31. Qxg7+ Ke8 32. Qg6+ Kd7 33. Qg7+ Ke8 34. Qg6+ Kd7 35. Qg7+ Be7 36. c4 Qf5 37. b4 Ke6 38. Rd1 Bf6 39. Rd6+ Kxd6 40. Qf7 Bd7 41. Bf4+ Kc6 42. b5+ Kc5 {0-1 (40) Ganguly,S (2636) -Eljanov,P (2650) Wijk aan Zee 2020}  ) ( 16. g3 $2 Bxg3 17. fxg3 Qxg3+ 18. Kh1 Nf4 19. Qf1 Nxd3 20. Qxd3 Qxh3+ 21. Kg1 Qg3+ 22. Kh1 e5 $1 { Black is taking over}  ) Nf4 16. Bxf4 {Unfortunately White has to give away his dark-squared bishop.} Bxf4 17. g3 Bd6 18. Ne3 {from here on the game obviously is not forced but let me illustrate to you a possible continuation} ( 19. N1h2 Rfe8 20. Ng4 f6 21. Qc2 Nf8 { it seems that Black is doing excellent here and is ready to fire away with e6-e5 and it's not clear what the white knight is doing on g4.}  ) Rfe8 19. Rad1 f6 20. Qc2 Nf8 21. Kg2 Rad8 22. h4 {with an interesting game, for example} Kh8 ( e5 $6 23. dxe5 fxe5 24. Qb3  ) 23. h5 e5 24. Nh4 $13 {This particular position I'd choose White.}  ) Bxe5 {the critical move} 14. dxe5 Ne4 {and Black has various possibilities to sacrifice the knight on e4 for at least two pawns and a strong centre.} 15. Bc2 $5 ( 16. f3 $146 {this direct move almost forces Black to sacrifice the piece.} Nxe5 ( Ng3 $6 17. Qf2 Nh5 18. g4 Nxe5 19. Rxe5 Qxe5 20. f4 $1 $16  ) ( f5 $5 $13  ) 17. fxe4 Nxd3 18. Qxd3 dxe4 { The game is very complex and for the sake of some clarity probably it's a good idea to return some of the material. If played out perfectly from both sides, it should end with a draw.} 19. Rxe4 ( 20. Qf1 f5 21. Nd2 Rad8 {looks too scary 